ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Cannot distinguish between two or more possible values in the current context.: A malignant, invasive embryonal neoplasm arising from the cerebellum. It occurs predominantly in children and has the tendency to metastasize via the cerebrospinal fluid pathways. Signs and symptoms include truncal ataxia, disturbed gait, lethargy, headache, and vomiting. There are four histologic variants: classic medulloblastoma, large cell/anaplastic medulloblastoma, desmoplastic/nodular medulloblastoma, and medulloblastoma with extensive nodularity.

Concepts.definition: Cannot distinguish between two or more possible values in the current context.

A malignant, invasive embryonal neoplasm arising from the cerebellum or posterior fossa. It occurs predominantly in children and has the tendency to metastasize via the cerebrospinal fluid pathways. Signs and symptoms include truncal ataxia, disturbed gait, lethargy, headache, and vomiting. There are four histologic variants: classic medulloblastoma, large cell/anaplastic medulloblastoma, desmoplastic/nodular medulloblastoma, and medulloblastoma with extensive nodularity.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Ductal carcinoma in situ (DCIS) is a carcinoma entirely confined to the mammary ducts. There is no evidence of invasion of the basement membrane. Currently, DCIS is classified into three categories: High-grade DCIS, intermediate-grade DCIS and low-grade DCIS. In this classification the DCIS grade is defined by a combination of nuclear grade, architectural growth pattern and presence of necrosis. The size of the lesion as well as the grade and the clearance margins play a major role in dictating the most appropriate therapy for DCIS. --2002

Concepts.definition: A breast carcinoma entirely confined to the mammary ducts. It is also known as DCIS. There is no evidence of invasion of the basement membrane. Currently, it is classified into three categories: High-grade DCIS, intermediate-grade DCIS and low-grade DCIS. In this classification the DCIS grade is defined by a combination of nuclear grade, architectural growth pattern and presence of necrosis. The size of the lesion as well as the grade and the clearance margins play a major role in dictating the most appropriate therapy for DCIS.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An aggressive, high-grade, and poorly differentiated carcinoma with neuroendocrine differentiation that arises from the colon or rectum.  It is characterized by the presence of malignant small cells.

Concepts.definition: An aggressive, high-grade, and poorly differentiated carcinoma with neuroendocrine differentiation that arises from the colon or rectum.  It is characterized by the presence of malignant small cells.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A morphologic finding indicating the presence of an architectural pattern dominated by the presence of small papillary structures.: A malignant tumor arising from epithelial cells. Carcinomas that arise from glandular epithelium are called adenocarcinomas, those that arise from squamous epithelium are called squamous cell carcinomas, and those that arise from transitional epithelium are called transitional cell carcinomas. Morphologically, the malignant epithelial cells may display abnormal mitotic figures, anaplasia, and necrosis. Carcinomas are graded by the degree of cellular differentiation as well, moderately, or poorly differentiated. Carcinomas invade the surrounding tissues and tend to metastasize to other anatomic sites. Lung carcinoma, skin carcinoma, breast carcinoma, colon carcinoma, and prostate carcinoma are the most frequently seen carcinomas.

Concepts.definition: A morphologic finding indicating the presence of a growth pattern dominated by the presence of small papillary structures.

A malignant tumor arising from epithelial cells. Carcinomas that arise from glandular epithelium are called adenocarcinomas, those that arise from squamous epithelium are called squamous cell carcinomas, and those that arise from transitional epithelium are called transitional cell carcinomas. Morphologically, the malignant epithelial cells may display abnormal mitotic figures, anaplasia, and necrosis. Carcinomas are graded by the degree of cellular differentiation as well, moderately, or poorly differentiated. Carcinomas invade the surrounding tissues and tend to metastasize to other anatomic sites. Lung carcinoma, skin carcinoma, breast carcinoma, colon carcinoma, and prostate carcinoma are the most frequently seen carcinomas.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A cystic epithelial neoplasm characterized by the presence of columnar mucin-producing epithelial cells, ovarian-type stroma formation, and a focal or extensive invasive carcinomatous component.

Concepts.longName: Pancreatic Mucinous-Cystic Neoplasm with an Associated Invasive Carcinoma
Concepts.definition: A cystic epithelial neoplasm characterized by the presence of columnar mucin-producing epithelial cells, ovarian-type stroma formation, and a focal or extensive invasive carcinomatous component.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A morphologic variant of minimally invasive lung adenocarcinoma characterized by tall columnar cells and mucin production.

Concepts.definition: A morphologic variant of minimally invasive lung adenocarcinoma characterized by tall columnar cells and mucin production.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Lung adenocarcinoma in situ characterized by the presence of type II pneumocyte and/or Clara cell differentiation. Almost all cases of lung adenocarcinoma in situ are non-mucinous.

Concepts.definition: Lung adenocarcinoma in situ characterized by the presence of type II pneumocyte and/or Clara cell differentiation. Almost all cases of lung adenocarcinoma in situ are non-mucinous.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A very rare lung adenocarcinoma in situ variant characterized by the presence of tall columnar cells with basal nuclei and abundant cytoplasmic mucin.

Concepts.definition: A very rare lung adenocarcinoma in situ variant characterized by the presence of tall columnar cells with basal nuclei and abundant cytoplasmic mucin.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A morphologic variant of lung adenocarcinoma characterized by the presence of mucin pools containing islands of well differentiated adenocarcinoma cells.

Concepts.definition: A morphologic variant of lung adenocarcinoma characterized by the presence of mucin pools containing islands of well differentiated adenocarcinoma cells.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A well-differentiated adenocarcinoma located in the lung periphery. It resembles colorectal adenocarcinoma with acinar and/or cribriform architecture and papillotubular structures.

Concepts.definition: A well-differentiated adenocarcinoma located in the lung periphery. It resembles colorectal adenocarcinoma with acinar and/or cribriform architecture and papillotubular structures.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A morphologic variant of bronchiolo-alveolar lung carcinoma characterized by the presence of Clara cells and/or type II cells.

Concepts.definition: A morphologic variant of minimally invasive lung  adenocarcinoma characterized by the presence of Clara cells and/or type II cells.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The state in which a substance has no tendency to flow under moderate stress; resists forces (such as compression) that tend to deform it; and retains a definite size and shape.: A common cancer characterized by the presence of malignant glandular cells.  Morphologically, adenocarcinomas are classified according to the growth pattern (e.g., papillary, alveolar) or according to the secreting product (e.g., mucinous, serous).  Representative examples of adenocarcinoma are ductal and lobular breast carcinoma, lung adenocarcinoma, renal cell carcinoma, hepatocellular carcinoma (hepatoma), colon adenocarcinoma, and prostate adenocarcinoma.

Concepts.definition: The state in which a substance has no tendency to flow under moderate stress; resists forces (such as compression) that tend to deform it; and retains a definite size and shape.

A common cancer characterized by the presence of malignant glandular cells.  Morphologically, adenocarcinomas are classified according to the growth pattern (e.g., papillary, alveolar) or according to the secreting product (e.g., mucinous, serous).  Representative examples of adenocarcinoma are ductal and lobular breast carcinoma, lung adenocarcinoma, renal cell carcinoma, hepatocellular carcinoma (hepatoma), colon adenocarcinoma, and prostate adenocarcinoma.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An aggressive, high-grade and poorly differentiated carcinoma with neuroendocrine differentiation that arises from the stomach.  It is characterized by the presence of malignant small cells.

Concepts.definition: An aggressive, high-grade and poorly differentiated carcinoma with neuroendocrine differentiation that arises from the stomach.  It is characterized by the presence of malignant small cells.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A rare adenocarcinoma that arises from the gastric mucosa and is characterized by the presence of prominent lymphocytic stromal infiltration and poorly formed tubular structures.

Concepts.definition: A rare adenocarcinoma that arises from the gastric mucosa and is characterized by the presence of prominent lymphocytic stromal infiltration and poorly formed tubular structures.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An adenocarcinoma with morphologic characteristics similar to hepatocellular carcinoma, arising from an anatomic site other than the liver.

Concepts.definition: An adenocarcinoma with morphologic characteristics similar to hepatocellular carcinoma, arising from an anatomic site other than the liver.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A carcinoma that arises from the stomach and is characterized by the presence of a malignant glandular epithelial component and a malignant neuroendocrine component.  At least 30 percent of either component should be present for the diagnosis to be made.

Concepts.definition: A carcinoma that arises from the stomach and is characterized by the presence of a malignant glandular epithelial component and a malignant neuroendocrine component.  At least 30 percent of either component should be present for the diagnosis to be made.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An insidious, locally aggressive, poorly circumscribed neoplasm arising from the deep soft tissues. It is characterized by the presence of elongated spindle-shaped fibroblasts, collagenous stroma formation, and an infiltrative growth pattern. It lacks metastatic potential.: A usually aggressive malignant neoplasm of the soft tissue or bone. It arises from muscle, fat, fibrous tissue, bone, cartilage, and blood vessels. Sarcomas occur in both children and adults. The prognosis depends largely on the degree of differentiation (grade) of the neoplasm. Representative subtypes are liposarcoma, leiomyosarcoma, osteosarcoma, and chondrosarcoma.

Concepts.definition: An insidious, locally aggressive, poorly circumscribed neoplasm arising from the deep soft tissues. It is characterized by the presence of elongated spindle-shaped fibroblasts, collagenous stroma formation, and an infiltrative growth pattern. It lacks metastatic potential.

A usually aggressive malignant neoplasm of the soft tissue or bone. It arises from muscle, fat, fibrous tissue, bone, cartilage, and blood vessels. Sarcomas occur in both children and adults. The prognosis depends largely on the degree of differentiation (grade) of the neoplasm. Representative subtypes are liposarcoma, leiomyosarcoma, osteosarcoma, and chondrosarcoma.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A carcinoma that arises from the digestive system and is characterized by the presence of a malignant glandular epithelial component and a malignant neuroendocrine component.  At least 30% of either component should be present for the diagnosis to be made.

Concepts.definition: A carcinoma that arises from the digestive system and is characterized by the presence of a malignant glandular epithelial component and a malignant neuroendocrine component. At least 30% of either component should be present for the diagnosis to be made.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A malignant epithelial neoplasm composed of large, atypical cells.: A malignant neuroendocrine neoplasm composed of cells containing secretory granules that stain positive for NSE and chromogranin.  The neoplastic cells are often round and form clusters or trabecular sheets.  Representative examples are small cell carcinoma, large cell neuroendocrine carcinoma, and Merkel cell carcinoma.

Concepts.definition: A malignant epithelial neoplasm composed of large, atypical cells.
A usually aggressive carcinoma composed of malignant cells exhibiting neuroendocrine differentiation.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A neuroendocrine carcinoma composed of small malignant cells which are often said to resemble "oat cells" under the microscope.  Small cell carcinoma most often affects the lungs.  Clinically, this is often a rapidly growing cancer that spreads to distant sites early.: A malignant neuroendocrine neoplasm composed of cells containing secretory granules that stain positive for NSE and chromogranin.  The neoplastic cells are often round and form clusters or trabecular sheets.  Representative examples are small cell carcinoma, large cell neuroendocrine carcinoma, and Merkel cell carcinoma.

Concepts.definition: An aggressive, high-grade, and poorly differentiated carcinoma with neuroendocrine differentiation. It is composed of malignant small cells.
A usually aggressive carcinoma composed of malignant cells exhibiting neuroendocrine differentiation.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Describes tumor cells that have lost some of the appearance of normal cells. They tend to grow and spread at a faster rate than well differentiated tumor cells.: A malignant neuroendocrine neoplasm composed of cells containing secretory granules that stain positive for NSE and chromogranin.  The neoplastic cells are often round and form clusters or trabecular sheets.  Representative examples are small cell carcinoma, large cell neuroendocrine carcinoma, and Merkel cell carcinoma.

Concepts.definition: Describes tumor cells that have lost some of the appearance of normal cells. They tend to grow and spread at a faster rate than well differentiated tumor cells.
A usually aggressive carcinoma composed of malignant cells exhibiting neuroendocrine differentiation.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Describes tumor cells that generally retain the appearance of normal cells and tend to grow and spread at a slower rate than undifferentiated or poorly differentiated tumor cells.: A malignant neuroendocrine neoplasm composed of cells containing secretory granules that stain positive for NSE and chromogranin.  The neoplastic cells are often round and form clusters or trabecular sheets.  Representative examples are small cell carcinoma, large cell neuroendocrine carcinoma, and Merkel cell carcinoma.

Concepts.definition: Describes tumor cells that generally retain the appearance of normal cells and tend to grow and spread at a slower rate than undifferentiated or poorly differentiated tumor cells.
A usually aggressive carcinoma composed of malignant cells exhibiting neuroendocrine differentiation.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Out of the ordinary, uncommon, or unexpected.: A characteristic to be considered; a distinct feature or element.: A common cancer characterized by the presence of malignant glandular cells.  Morphologically, adenocarcinomas are classified according to the growth pattern (e.g., papillary, alveolar) or according to the secreting product (e.g., mucinous, serous).  Representative examples of adenocarcinoma are ductal and lobular breast carcinoma, lung adenocarcinoma, renal cell carcinoma, hepatocellular carcinoma (hepatoma), colon adenocarcinoma, and prostate adenocarcinoma.

Concepts.definition: Out of the ordinary, uncommon, or unexpected.
A characteristic to be considered; a distinct feature or element.

A common cancer characterized by the presence of malignant glandular cells.  Morphologically, adenocarcinomas are classified according to the growth pattern (e.g., papillary, alveolar) or according to the secreting product (e.g., mucinous, serous).  Representative examples of adenocarcinoma are ductal and lobular breast carcinoma, lung adenocarcinoma, renal cell carcinoma, hepatocellular carcinoma (hepatoma), colon adenocarcinoma, and prostate adenocarcinoma.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Pancreatic Intraductal Papillary Mucinous Neoplasm, Gastric-Type

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Pancreatic Intraductal Papillary Mucinous Neoplasm, Gastric-Type
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A pancreatic intraductal papillary mucinous neoplasm characterized by the presence of neoplastic epithelial cells that are similar to gastric foveolar epithelial cells.

Concepts.longName: Pancreatic Intraductal Papillary Mucinous Neoplasm, Gastric-Type
Concepts.definition: A pancreatic intraductal papillary mucinous neoplasm characterized by the presence of neoplastic epithelial cells that are similar to gastric foveolar epithelial cells.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Extrahepatic Bile Duct Adenocarcinoma, Biliary Type

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Extrahepatic Bile Duct Adenocarcinoma, Biliary Type
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A well or moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma that arises from the extrahepatic bile ducts.  It is characterized by the presence of malignant tubular glands.

Concepts.longName: Extrahepatic Bile Duct Adenocarcinoma, Biliary Type
Concepts.definition: A well or moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma that arises from the extrahepatic bile ducts.  It is characterized by the presence of malignant tubular glands.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An adenocarcinoma arising from epithelium which has undergone intestinal metaplasia. Representative examples include gastric, gallbladder, and ampulla of Vater intestinal type adenocarcinomas.

Concepts.definition: An adenocarcinoma arising from epithelium which has undergone intestinal metaplasia. Representative examples include gastric, gallbladder, and ampulla of Vater intestinal type adenocarcinomas.

PermissibleValues.value: Mucinous cystic neoplasm with an associated invasive carcinoma

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A mucinous cystic neoplasm that arises from the intrahepatic or extrahepatic bile ducts and it is associated with an invasive carcinomatous component.

Concepts.longName: Bile Duct Mucinous Cystic Neoplasm with an Associated Invasive Carcinoma
Concepts.definition: A mucinous cystic neoplasm that arises from the intrahepatic or extrahepatic bile ducts and it is associated with an invasive carcinomatous component.

PermissibleValues.value: Intraductal papillary neoplasm with an associated invasive carcinoma
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Bile Duct Papillary Neoplasm with an Associated Invasive Carcinoma

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Bile Duct Papillary Neoplasm with an Associated Invasive Carcinoma
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A papillary epithelial neoplasm that arises from the epithelium of the intrahepatic or extrahepatic bile ducts and it is associated with an invasive carcinomatous component.  For intraductal papillary neoplasms of the intrahepatic bile ducts, the carcinomatous component is an intrahepatic cholangiocarcinoma; for intraductal papillary neoplasms of the extrahepatic bile ducts, the carcinomatous component is an adenocarcinoma.

Concepts.longName: Bile Duct Intraductal Papillary Neoplasm with an Associated Invasive Carcinoma
Concepts.definition: An intraductal papillary neoplasm that arises from the epithelium of the intrahepatic or extrahepatic bile ducts and it is associated with an invasive carcinomatous component.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A rare tumor containing unequivocal elements of both hepatocellular and cholangiocarcinoma that are intimately admixed.  This tumor should be distinguished from separate hepatocellular carcinoma and cholangiocarcinoma arising in the same liver.  The prognosis of this tumor is poor.

Concepts.definition: A rare tumor containing unequivocal elements of both hepatocellular and cholangiocarcinoma that are intimately admixed.  This tumor should be distinguished from separate hepatocellular carcinoma and cholangiocarcinoma arising in the same liver.  The prognosis of this tumor is poor.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Not characterized in any other way.: A malignant, usually aggressive tumor composed of atypical, neoplastic melanocytes. Most often, melanomas arise in the skin (cutaneous melanomas) and include the following histologic subtypes: superficial spreading melanoma, nodular melanoma, acral lentiginous melanoma, and lentigo maligna melanoma. Cutaneous melanomas may arise from acquired or congenital melanocytic or dysplastic nevi. Melanomas may also arise in other anatomic sites including the gastrointestinal system, eye, urinary tract, and reproductive system. Melanomas frequently metastasize to lymph nodes, liver, lungs, and brain.

Concepts.definition: Not characterized in any other way.

A malignant, usually aggressive tumor composed of atypical, neoplastic melanocytes. Most often, melanomas arise in the skin (cutaneous melanomas) and include the following histologic subtypes: superficial spreading melanoma, nodular melanoma, acral lentiginous melanoma, and lentigo maligna melanoma. Cutaneous melanomas may arise from acquired or congenital melanocytic or dysplastic nevi. Melanomas may also arise in other anatomic sites including the gastrointestinal system, eye, urinary tract, and reproductive system. Melanomas frequently metastasize to lymph nodes, liver, lungs, and brain.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A rare variant of melanoma occurring mostly in adults in their fifth decade. Morphologically it resembles an ordinary compound or dermal nevus.

Concepts.definition: A rare variant of cutaneous melanoma occurring mostly in adults in their fifth decade. Morphologically it resembles an ordinary compound or dermal nevus.

PermissibleValues.value: Melanoma arising in a giant congenital nevus
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Melanoma Arising in Giant Congenital Nevus

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Melanoma Arising in Giant Congenital Nevus
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A melanoma arising in a giant congenital melanocytic nevus. The risk of developing a melanoma in a giant congenital melanocytic nevus has been reported to be between 5% and 50%. The incidence of developing melanoma is higher before the age of 10 and in adult life.

Concepts.longName: Melanoma Arising in Giant Congenital Nevus
Concepts.definition: A melanoma arising in a giant congenital melanocytic nevus. The risk of developing a melanoma in a giant congenital melanocytic nevus has been reported to be between 5% and 50%. The incidence of developing melanoma is higher before the age of 10 and in adult life.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A melanoma of the skin resembling a benign blue nevus.

Concepts.definition: A rare melanoma which develops in a pre-existing blue nevus. It occurs more frequently on the scalp, face, orbit, back, buttocks, extremities, hands, and feet.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A melanoma of the skin characterized by a proliferation of atypical spindled melanocytes in the dermis, in a background of abundant collagen. It usually presents as an amelanotic raised nodular lesion.

Concepts.definition: A melanoma of the skin characterized by a proliferation of atypical spindled melanocytes in the dermis, in a background of abundant collagen. It usually presents as an amelanotic raised nodular lesion.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A form of melanoma occurring most often on the plantar, palmar, subungual, and periungual skin.  It presents as a pigmented macular lesion with irregular borders.  Morphologically, it consists of atypical spindled and dendritic melanocytes.  The epidermis is often hyperplastic and there is pagetoid infiltration of the epidermis by anaplastic cells.

Concepts.definition: A form of melanoma occurring most often on the plantar, palmar, subungual, and periungual skin.  It presents as a pigmented macular lesion with irregular borders.  Morphologically, it consists of atypical spindled and dendritic melanocytes.  The epidermis is often hyperplastic and there is pagetoid infiltration of the epidermis by anaplastic cells.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: (A melanoma of the skin characterized by single cell infiltration of the papillary dermis by atypical melanocytes, in a background of lentigo maligna changes.

Concepts.definition: A melanoma of the skin characterized by single cell infiltration of the papillary dermis by atypical melanocytes, in a background of lentigo maligna changes.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An aggressive form of melanoma, frequently metastasizing to the lymph nodes. It presents as a papular or nodular raised skin lesion. It comprises approximately 10-15% of melanomas. Morphologically, it often displays an epithelioid appearance.

Concepts.definition: An aggressive form of melanoma, frequently metastasizing to the lymph nodes.  It presents as a papular or nodular raised skin lesion.  It comprises approximately 10-15% of melanomas.  Morphologically, it often displays an epithelioid appearance.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A type of melanoma that typically occurs in light-skinned individuals ranging in age from young adults to the elderly.  Risk factors include extensive sun exposure during childhood, a family history of melanoma, and the presence of dysplastic nevi.

Concepts.definition: A type of melanoma that typically occurs in light-skinned individuals ranging in age from young adults to the elderly.  Risk factors include extensive sun exposure during childhood, a family history of melanoma, and the presence of dysplastic nevi.

PermissibleValues.value: Seromucinous borderline tumor/atypical proliferative seromucinous tumor with microinvasion
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Borderline Ovarian Seromucinous Tumor/Atypical Proliferative Ovarian Seromucinous Tumor with Microinvasion

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Borderline Ovarian Seromucinous Tumor/Atypical Proliferative Ovarian Seromucinous Tumor with Microinvasion
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A low grade ovarian epithelial neoplasm characterized by the presence of neoplastic serous and mucinous epithelial cells, atypia, and the presence of microinvasion of the ovarian stroma.

Concepts.longName: Borderline Ovarian Seromucinous Tumor/Atypical Proliferative Ovarian Seromucinous Tumor with Microinvasion
Concepts.definition: A low grade ovarian epithelial neoplasm characterized by the presence of atypical neoplastic serous and mucinous cells. Microinvasion of the ovarian stroma is present.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An endometrioid adenocarcinoma arising from the ovary.  It comprises 10% to 25% of all primary ovarian carcinomas.  Grossly, endometrioid carcinoma may present as a cystic or solid mass.  Microscopically, the tumor greatly resembles the appearance of the ordinary type of endometrial adenocarcinoma.  As a group, endometrioid carcinoma has a prognosis twice as good as that of serous or mucinous carcinoma.

Concepts.definition: An endometrioid adenocarcinoma arising from the ovary.  It comprises 10% to 25% of all primary ovarian carcinomas.  Grossly, endometrioid carcinoma may present as a cystic or solid mass.  Microscopically, the tumor greatly resembles the appearance of the ordinary type of endometrial adenocarcinoma.  As a group, endometrioid carcinoma has a prognosis twice as good as that of serous or mucinous carcinoma.

PermissibleValues.value: Serous borderline tumor-micropapillary variant/noninvasive low-grade serous carcinoma
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: SEROUS TUMOR OF LOW MALIGNANT POTENTIAL

ValueMeaning.preferredName: SEROUS TUMOR OF LOW MALIGNANT POTENTIAL
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A non-invasive serous neoplasm that arises from the ovary and shows micropapillary and/or cribriform architectural patterns.  It is composed of round epithelial cells with scant cytoplasm and moderate nuclear atypia.

Concepts.longName: Borderline Ovarian Serous Tumor-Micropapillary Variant/Non-Invasive Low Grade Ovarian Serous Carcinoma
Concepts.definition: A non-invasive serous neoplasm that arises from the ovary and shows micropapillary and/or cribriform architectural patterns.  It is composed of round epithelial cells with scant cytoplasm and moderate nuclear atypia.

ValueMeaning.changeDescription: Added concept, verified with EVS team - DW 03-21-2019

PermissibleValues.value: Serous borderline tumor/atypical proliferative serous tumor with microinvasion

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An ovarian epithelial tumor characterized by the presence of neoplastic serous epithelial cells, atypia, and microinvasion of the ovarian stroma.

Concepts.longName: Borderline Ovarian Serous Tumor/Atypical Proliferative Ovarian Serous Tumor with Microinvasion
Concepts.definition: A low grade ovarian epithelial neoplasm characterized by the presence of neoplastic serous epithelial cells, atypia, and microinvasion of the ovarian stroma.

PermissibleValues.value: Serous borderline tumor/atypical proliferative serous tumor
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Borderline Ovarian Serous Tumor/Atypical Proliferative Ovarian Serous Tumor

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Borderline Ovarian Serous Tumor/Atypical Proliferative Ovarian Serous Tumor
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A non-invasive serous neoplasm that arises from the ovary and shows greater cellular proliferation and cytologic atypia as compared to benign ovarian serous tumors, but less as compared to low-grade ovarian serous carcinoma.

Concepts.longName: Borderline Ovarian Serous Tumor/Atypical Proliferative Ovarian Serous Tumor
Concepts.definition: A non-invasive serous neoplasm that arises from the ovary and shows greater cellular proliferation and cytologic atypia as compared to benign ovarian serous tumors, but less as compared to low-grade ovarian serous carcinoma.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A non-invasive serous carcinoma arising from the fallopian tube.

Concepts.definition: A non-invasive serous carcinoma arising from the fallopian tube.

PermissibleValues.value: Mucinous borderline tumor/atypical proliferative mucinous tumor with microinvasion
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Borderline Ovarian Mucinous Tumor/Atypical Proliferative Ovarian Mucinous Tumor with Microinvasion

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Borderline Ovarian Mucinous Tumor/Atypical Proliferative Ovarian Mucinous Tumor with Microinvasion
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A low grade ovarian epithelial neoplasm characterized by the presence of neoplastic mucinous epithelial cells, atypia, and microinvasion of the ovarian stroma.

Concepts.longName: Borderline Ovarian Mucinous Tumor/Atypical Proliferative Ovarian Mucinous Tumor with Microinvasion
Concepts.definition: A low grade ovarian epithelial neoplasm characterized by the presence of neoplastic mucinous epithelial cells, atypia, and microinvasion of the ovarian stroma.

PermissibleValues.value: Mucinous borderline tumor/atypical proliferative mucinous tumor with intraepithelial carcinoma
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Borderline Ovarian Mucinous Tumor/Atypical Proliferative Ovarian Mucinous Tumor with Intraepithelial Carcinoma

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Borderline Ovarian Mucinous Tumor/Atypical Proliferative Ovarian Mucinous Tumor with Intraepithelial Carcinoma
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A low grade ovarian epithelial neoplasm characterized by the presence of neoplastic mucinous epithelial cells, atypia, and the presence of intraepithelial carcinoma.

Concepts.longName: Borderline Ovarian Mucinous Tumor/Atypical Proliferative Ovarian Mucinous Tumor with Intraepithelial Carcinoma
Concepts.definition: A low grade ovarian epithelial neoplasm characterized by the presence of neoplastic mucinous epithelial cells, atypia, and the presence of intraepithelial carcinoma.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A carcinoma which has metastasized from an unknown primary anatomic site.

Concepts.definition: A carcinoma which has metastasized from an unknown primary anatomic site.

ValueMeaning.changeDescription: Concept annotation added for UPitt/TCGA.  Ylu, 02/24/2015.

PermissibleValues.value: Brenner tumor, borderline/atypical proliferative Brenner tumor

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A Brenner tumor of the ovary characterized by papillary structures, nuclear cytologic atypia, and absense of stromal invasion.

Concepts.definition: A neoplasm of low malignant potential arising from the ovary. It is characterized by the presence of neoplastic atypical urothelial-type cells in a fibrotic stroma without evidence of invasion.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A malignant mixed epithelial neoplasm that arises from the ovary and is composed predominantly of serous and endocervical-type mucinous epithelium.

Concepts.definition: A malignant mixed epithelial neoplasm that arises from the ovary and is composed predominantly of serous and endocervical-type mucinous cells.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An ovarian malignant germ cell tumor characterized by the presence of at least two different germ cell tumor components. The most common combination of germ cell tumors is dysgerminoma and yolk sac tumor.

Concepts.definition: An ovarian malignant germ cell tumor characterized by the presence of at least two different germ cell tumor components. The most common combination of germ cell tumors is dysgerminoma and yolk sac tumor.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Ovarian Dermoid Cyst with Secondary Carcinoma

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Ovarian Dermoid Cyst with Secondary Carcinoma
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A secondary carcinoma that has developed in an ovarian dermoid cyst.  In the majority of cases, the secondary carcinoma is a squamous cell carcinoma.

Concepts.longName: Ovarian Dermoid Cyst with Secondary Carcinoma
Concepts.definition: A secondary carcinoma that has developed in an ovarian dermoid cyst.  In the majority of cases, the secondary carcinoma is a squamous cell carcinoma.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An immature teratoma arising from the ovary.  It usually affects females in their first two decades of life.

Concepts.definition: An immature teratoma arising from the ovary.  It usually affects females in their first two decades of life.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A usually rapidly growing malignant germ cell tumor arising from the ovary.  It usually occurs in children and adolescents.  Signs and symptoms include abdominal pain and a large abdominal or pelvic mass.  The serum alpha-fetoprotein is almost always elevated preoperatively.  Morphologically, there is marked heterogeneity due to numerous patterns of differentiation coexisting in the same tumor.  The most common pattern is reticular.

Concepts.definition: A usually rapidly growing malignant germ cell tumor arising from the ovary.  It usually occurs in children and adolescents.  Signs and symptoms include abdominal pain and a large abdominal or pelvic mass.  The serum alpha-fetoprotein is almost always elevated preoperatively.  Morphologically, there is marked heterogeneity due to numerous patterns of differentiation coexisting in the same tumor.  The most common pattern is reticular.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A malignant germ cell tumor arising from the ovary.  Morphologically, it is identical to seminoma and consists of a monotonous population of germ cells with abundant pale cytoplasm and uniform nuclei.  The stroma invariably contains chronic inflammatory cells, mostly T-lymphocytes. It responds to chemotherapy or radiotherapy and the prognosis relates to the tumor stage.

Concepts.definition: A malignant germ cell tumor arising from the ovary.  Morphologically, it is identical to seminoma and consists of a monotonous population of germ cells with abundant pale cytoplasm and uniform nuclei.  The stroma invariably contains chronic inflammatory cells, mostly T-lymphocytes. It responds to chemotherapy or radiotherapy and the prognosis relates to the tumor stage.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Juvenile Type Ovarian Granulosa Cell Tumor

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Juvenile Type Ovarian Granulosa Cell Tumor
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A granulosa cell tumor that affects females in the first three decades of life.  In young girls it may present with pseudoprecocity.  In women during reproductive years, it may present with menstrual abnormalities.

Concepts.definition: An ovarian granulosa cell tumor that affects females in the first three decades of life. It presents unilaterally as stage I disease in the vast majority of cases. The prognosis is usually good.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Adult Type Ovarian Granulosa Cell Tumor

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Adult Type Ovarian Granulosa Cell Tumor
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A granulosa cell tumor that affects middle aged or postmenopausal women.  Patients may present with uterine bleeding.

Concepts.definition: A low-grade malignant sex cord-stromal tumor that occurs in the ovary and affects middle aged to post-menopausal women. It is composed of granulosa cells in an often fibrothecomatous stroma. The neoplastic cells may form various patterns including the microfollicular, which is characterized by the presence of Call-Exner bodies, macrofollicular, insular, trabecular, and diffuse pattern. Signs and symptoms include abdominal mass, hemoperitoneum, and ascites. Estrogenic and rarely androgenic manifestations may be present. The vast majority of cases present as stage I tumors; however, all tumors have a potential for aggressive clinical course.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An aggressive carcinoma arising from the ovary.  Most patients present with advanced disease.  Microscopically, it is characterized by significant cytologic atypia, increased mitotic activity, and necrosis.  The prognosis is usually poor.

Concepts.definition: An aggressive carcinoma arising from the ovary.  Most patients present with advanced disease.  Microscopically, it is characterized by significant cytologic atypia, increased mitotic activity, and necrosis.  The prognosis is usually poor.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A carcinoma that arises from the ovary and is characterized by the presence of malignant epithelial cells that resemble malignant urothelial cells.  There is no morphologic evidence of a benign or borderline Brenner tumor component present.

Concepts.definition: A carcinoma that arises from the ovary and is characterized by the presence of malignant epithelial cells that resemble malignant urothelial cells.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A usually high grade squamous cell carcinoma that arises from the ovary and is not associated with a germ cell tumor.  The prognosis is poor.

Concepts.definition: A usually high grade squamous cell carcinoma that arises from the ovary and is not associated with a germ cell tumor.  The prognosis is poor.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Ovarian Small Cell Carcinoma, Hypercalcemic Type

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Ovarian Small Cell Carcinoma, Hypercalcemic Type
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An undifferentiated small cell carcinoma that arises from the ovary and is associated with hypercalcemia.  Electron microscopic studies show neurosecretory granules are either absent or, when present, are in small numbers.

Concepts.longName: Ovarian Small Cell Carcinoma, Hypercalcemic Type
Concepts.definition: An undifferentiated small cell carcinoma that arises from the ovary and is associated with hypercalcemia.  Electron microscopic studies show neurosecretory granules are either absent or, when present, are in small numbers.

PermissibleValues.value: Mucinous borderline tumor/atypical proliferative mucinous tumor
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Borderline Ovarian Mucinous Tumor/Atypical Proliferative Ovarian Mucinous Tumor

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Borderline Ovarian Mucinous Tumor/Atypical Proliferative Ovarian Mucinous Tumor
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A non-invasive neoplasm that arises from the ovary and is composed of gastrointestinal-type, mucin-containing epithelial cells.  It shows greater cellular proliferation and cytologic atypia as compared to benign ovarian mucinous tumors.

Concepts.longName: Borderline Ovarian Mucinous Tumor/Atypical Proliferative Ovarian Mucinous Tumor
Concepts.definition: A non-invasive neoplasm that arises from the ovary and is composed of gastrointestinal-type, mucin-containing epithelial cells.  It shows greater cellular proliferation and cytologic atypia as compared to benign ovarian mucinous tumors.

PermissibleValues.value: Clear cell borderline tumor/atypical proliferative clear cell tumor
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Borderline Ovarian Clear Cell Tumor/Atypical Proliferative Ovarian Clear Cell Tumor

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Borderline Ovarian Clear Cell Tumor/Atypical Proliferative Ovarian Clear Cell Tumor
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A non-invasive clear cell adenofibromatous neoplasm that arises from the ovary. It is characterized by the presence of atypia in the glandular epithelium.

Concepts.longName: Borderline Ovarian Clear Cell Tumor/Atypical Proliferative Ovarian Clear Cell Tumor
Concepts.definition: A non-invasive clear cell adenofibromatous neoplasm that arises from the ovary. It is characterized by the presence of atypia in the glandular epithelium.

PermissibleValues.value: Endometrioid borderline tumor/atypical proliferative endometrioid tumor

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A neoplasm of low malignant potential arising from the ovary. It is characterized by the presence of glandular or cystic spaces which contain atypical glandular epithelial cells resembling endometrial cells. The surrounding ovarian stroma is often fibrotic. There is no evidence of stromal invasion.

Concepts.longName: Borderline Ovarian Endometrioid Tumor/Atypical Proliferative Ovarian Endometrioid Tumor
Concepts.definition: An epithelial neoplasm that arises from the ovary characterized by the presence of glandular or cystic spaces which contain atypical glandular epithelial cells resembling endometrial cells. The surrounding ovarian stroma is often fibrotic. There is no evidence of stromal invasion.

PermissibleValues.value: Seromucinous borderline tumor/atypical proliferative seromucinous tumor

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A low grade ovarian epithelial tumor composed of an admixture of two or more of the five major cell types: serous, mucinous, endometrioid, clear cell, and Brenner/transitional.  The second or second and third cell types must comprise alone or together at least 10% of the tumor epithelium. The majority of patients present with stage I tumor and a minority present with bilateral disease. Morphologically, it shows papillae with detached cell clusters.  Microinvasion may be seen rarely. (WHO 2003)

Concepts.longName: Borderline Ovarian Seromucinous Tumor/Atypical Proliferative Ovarian Seromucinous Tumor
Concepts.definition: A low grade, non-invasive ovarian epithelial neoplasm characterized by the presence of atypical neoplastic serous and mucinous cells.

PermissibleValues.value: Endometrioid borderline tumor/atypical proliferative endometrioid tumor with microinvasion
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Borderline Ovarian Endometrioid Tumor/Atypical Proliferative Ovarian Endometrioid Tumor with Microinvasion

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Borderline Ovarian Endometrioid Tumor/Atypical Proliferative Ovarian Endometrioid Tumor with Microinvasion
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A low grade ovarian epithelial neoplasm characterized by the presence of glandular or cystic spaces which contain atypical glandular epithelial cells resembling endometrial cells, and microinvasion of the ovarian stroma.

Concepts.longName: Borderline Ovarian Endometrioid Tumor/Atypical Proliferative Ovarian Endometrioid Tumor with Microinvasion
Concepts.definition: A low grade ovarian epithelial neoplasm characterized by the presence of glandular or cystic spaces which contain atypical glandular epithelial cells resembling endometrial cells. Microinvasion of the ovarian stroma is present.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Borderline Ovarian Mixed Epithelial Tumor/Atypical Proliferative Ovarian Mixed Epithelial Tumor

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Borderline Ovarian Mixed Epithelial Tumor/Atypical Proliferative Ovarian Mixed Epithelial Tumor
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A low grade, non-invasive mixed epithelial proliferative neoplasm that arises from the ovary. In most cases is composed of serous and endocervical-type mucinous cells.

Concepts.longName: Borderline Ovarian Mixed Epithelial Tumor/Atypical Proliferative Ovarian Mixed Epithelial Tumor
Concepts.definition: A low grade, non-invasive mixed epithelial proliferative neoplasm that arises from the ovary. In most cases is composed of serous and endocervical-type mucinous cells.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A well differentiated squamous cell carcinoma arising from the oral cavity.  It is an exophytic, warty, slow growing tumor, usually affecting older males.  Chronic use of smokeless tobacco is associated with the development of verrucous carcinoma in the oral cavity.  Five year disease-free survival rates between 80% and 90% have been reported in patients who underwent extensive surgical removal of the tumor.

Concepts.definition: A well differentiated squamous cell carcinoma arising from the oral cavity.  It is an exophytic, warty, slow growing tumor, usually affecting older males.  Chronic use of smokeless tobacco is associated with the development of verrucous carcinoma in the oral cavity.  Five year disease-free survival rates between 80% and 90% have been reported in patients who underwent extensive surgical removal of the tumor.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A nonkeratinizing carcinoma which occurs predominantly in the nasopharynx but also in the tonsils and rarely in other anatomic sites.  It is characterized by the presence of large malignant cells with vesicular nuclei, prominent nucleoli, syncytial growth pattern, and a lymphoplasmacytic infiltrate.

Concepts.definition: A nonkeratinizing carcinoma which occurs predominantly in the nasopharynx but also in the tonsils and rarely in other anatomic sites.  It is characterized by the presence of large malignant cells with vesicular nuclei, prominent nucleoli, syncytial growth pattern, and a lymphoplasmacytic infiltrate.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A sebaceous carcinoma that arises from the skin in the head and neck.

Concepts.definition: A sebaceous carcinoma that arises from the head and neck region.

PermissibleValues.value: Poorly differentiated carcinoma, large cell neuroendocrine
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Head and Neck Large Cell Neuroendocrine Carcinoma

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Head and Neck Large Cell Neuroendocrine Carcinoma
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A large cell neuroendocrine carcinoma that arises from the head and neck.

Concepts.longName: Head and Neck Large Cell Neuroendocrine Carcinoma
Concepts.definition: A large cell neuroendocrine carcinoma that arises from the head and neck.

PermissibleValues.value: Poorly differentiated carcinoma, small cell neuroendocrine
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Head and Neck Small Cell Carcinoma

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Head and Neck Small Cell Carcinoma
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A small cell carcinoma that arises from the head and neck.

Concepts.longName: Head and Neck Small Cell Neuroendocrine Carcinoma
Concepts.definition: A small cell neuroendocrine carcinoma that arises from the head and neck.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A tumor at the original site of origin.: A carcinoma arising from squamous epithelial cells.  Morphologically, it is characterized by the proliferation of atypical, often pleomorphic squamous cells.  Squamous cell carcinomas are graded by the degree of cellular differentiation as well, moderately, or poorly differentiated.  Well differentiated carcinomas are usually associated with keratin production and the presence of intercellular bridges between adjacent cells.  Representative examples are lung squamous cell carcinoma, skin squamous cell carcinoma, and cervical squamous cell carcinoma.

Concepts.definition: A tumor at the original site of origin.

A carcinoma arising from squamous epithelial cells.  Morphologically, it is characterized by the proliferation of atypical, often pleomorphic squamous cells.  Squamous cell carcinomas are graded by the degree of cellular differentiation as well, moderately, or poorly differentiated.  Well differentiated carcinomas are usually associated with keratin production and the presence of intercellular bridges between adjacent cells.  Representative examples are lung squamous cell carcinoma, skin squamous cell carcinoma, and cervical squamous cell carcinoma.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A carcinoma morphologically characterized the presence of cuboidal mucous cells, goblet-like mucous cells, squamoid cells, cystic changes, and a fibrotic stromal formation. It can occur in several anatomic sites, including parotid gland, oral cavity, paranasal sinus, skin, breast, lung, larynx, and lacrimal ducts. It is classified as low or high grade.

Concepts.definition: A carcinoma morphologically characterized the presence of cuboidal mucous cells, goblet-like mucous cells, squamoid cells, cystic changes, and a fibrotic stromal formation. It can occur in several anatomic sites, including parotid gland, oral cavity, paranasal sinus, skin, breast, lung, larynx, and lacrimal ducts. It is classified as low or high grade.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A rare, highly aggressive and lethal carcinoma that affects children and young adults.  It arises from midline epithelial structures, most commonly the head, neck, and mediastinum.  It is a poorly differentiated carcinoma and is characterized by mutations and rearrangement of the NUT gene.  A balanced translocation t(15;19) is present that results in the creation of a fusion gene involving the NUT gene, most commonly BRD4-NUT fusion gene.

Concepts.definition: A rare, highly aggressive and lethal carcinoma that affects children and young adults.  It arises from midline epithelial structures, most commonly the head, neck, and mediastinum.  It is a poorly differentiated carcinoma and is characterized by mutations and rearrangement of the NUT gene.  A balanced translocation t(15;19) is present that results in the creation of a fusion gene involving the NUT gene, most commonly BRD4-NUT fusion gene.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A rare, highly aggressive carcinoma that arises from the sinonasal tract.  It is characterized by the presence of small to medium size malignant cells.  The prognosis is poor.

Concepts.definition: A rare, highly aggressive carcinoma that arises from the sinonasal tract.  It is characterized by the presence of small to medium size malignant cells.  The prognosis is poor.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A carcinoma that arises from the minor salivary glands.  Representative examples include adenoid cystic carcinoma, acinic cell carcinoma, polymorphous low grade adenocarcinoma, and mucinous adenocarcinoma.

Concepts.definition: A carcinoma that arises from the minor salivary glands.  Representative examples include adenoid cystic carcinoma, acinic cell carcinoma, polymorphous low grade adenocarcinoma, and mucinous adenocarcinoma.

PermissibleValues.value: Large cell neuroendocrine carcinoma, HPV positive
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Human Papillomavirus Positive Large Cell Neuroendocrine Carcinoma

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Human Papillomavirus Positive Large Cell Neuroendocrine Carcinoma
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Indicates that human papillomavirus has been detected in a sample.: A usually aggressive carcinoma composed of large malignant cells which display neuroendocrine characteristics. It is characterized by the presence of high mitotic activity and necrotic changes. The vast majority of cases are positive for neuron-specific enolase. Representative examples include lung, breast, cervical, and thymic neuroendocrine carcinomas.

Concepts.definition: Indicates that human papillomavirus has been detected in a sample.
An aggressive, high-grade, and poorly differentiated carcinoma with neuroendocrine differentiation. It is composed of malignant large cells.

PermissibleValues.value: Large cell neuroendocrine carcinoma, HPV negative
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Human Papillomavirus Negative Large Cell Neuroendocrine Carcinoma

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Human Papillomavirus Negative Large Cell Neuroendocrine Carcinoma
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Indicates that human papillomavirus has not been detected in a sample.: A usually aggressive carcinoma composed of large malignant cells which display neuroendocrine characteristics. It is characterized by the presence of high mitotic activity and necrotic changes. The vast majority of cases are positive for neuron-specific enolase. Representative examples include lung, breast, cervical, and thymic neuroendocrine carcinomas.

Concepts.definition: Indicates that human papillomavirus has not been detected in a sample.
An aggressive, high-grade, and poorly differentiated carcinoma with neuroendocrine differentiation. It is composed of malignant large cells.

PermissibleValues.value: Small cell neuroendocrine carcinoma, HPV positive
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Human Papillomavirus Positive Small Cell Carcinoma

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Human Papillomavirus Positive Small Cell Carcinoma
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Indicates that human papillomavirus has been detected in a sample.: A neuroendocrine carcinoma composed of small malignant cells which are often said to resemble "oat cells" under the microscope.  Small cell carcinoma most often affects the lungs.  Clinically, this is often a rapidly growing cancer that spreads to distant sites early.

Concepts.definition: Indicates that human papillomavirus has been detected in a sample.
An aggressive, high-grade, and poorly differentiated carcinoma with neuroendocrine differentiation. It is composed of malignant small cells.

PermissibleValues.value: Small cell neuroendocrine carcinoma, HPV negative
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Human Papillomavirus Negative Small Cell Carcinoma

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Human Papillomavirus Negative Small Cell Carcinoma
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Indicates that human papillomavirus has not been detected in a sample.: A neuroendocrine carcinoma composed of small malignant cells which are often said to resemble "oat cells" under the microscope.  Small cell carcinoma most often affects the lungs.  Clinically, this is often a rapidly growing cancer that spreads to distant sites early.

Concepts.definition: Indicates that human papillomavirus has not been detected in a sample.
An aggressive, high-grade, and poorly differentiated carcinoma with neuroendocrine differentiation. It is composed of malignant small cells.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A rare, low-grade exophytic adenocarcinoma with papillary growth that arises from the epithelium of the nasopharynx.  If it is completely removed, the prognosis is excellent.

Concepts.definition: A low-grade exophytic adenocarcinoma with papillary growth that arises from the epithelium of the nasopharynx. If it is completely removed, the prognosis is excellent.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An operation in which a term denies or inverts the meaning of another term or construction.: An exocrine gland that secretes saliva. Salivary glands are mostly located in and around the oral cavity.: A common cancer characterized by the presence of malignant glandular cells.  Morphologically, adenocarcinomas are classified according to the growth pattern (e.g., papillary, alveolar) or according to the secreting product (e.g., mucinous, serous).  Representative examples of adenocarcinoma are ductal and lobular breast carcinoma, lung adenocarcinoma, renal cell carcinoma, hepatocellular carcinoma (hepatoma), colon adenocarcinoma, and prostate adenocarcinoma.

Concepts.definition: An operation in which a term denies or inverts the meaning of another term or construction.
An exocrine gland that secretes saliva. Salivary glands are mostly located in and around the oral cavity.

A common cancer characterized by the presence of malignant glandular cells.  Morphologically, adenocarcinomas are classified according to the growth pattern (e.g., papillary, alveolar) or according to the secreting product (e.g., mucinous, serous).  Representative examples of adenocarcinoma are ductal and lobular breast carcinoma, lung adenocarcinoma, renal cell carcinoma, hepatocellular carcinoma (hepatoma), colon adenocarcinoma, and prostate adenocarcinoma.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A squamous cell carcinoma arising from the hypopharynx.  Signs and symptoms include dysphagia, hemoptysis, and the presence of a neck mass.

Concepts.definition: A squamous cell carcinoma arising from the hypopharynx.  Signs and symptoms include dysphagia, hemoptysis, and the presence of a neck mass.

PermissibleValues.value: Oropharyngeal squamous cell carcinoma, HPV status unknown
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Oropharyngeal Carcinoma Human Papillomavirus Status Unknown Squamous Cell Carcinoma

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Oropharyngeal Carcinoma Human Papillomavirus Status Unknown Squamous Cell Carcinoma
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Carcinoma, predominantly squamous cell, arising from the epithelial cells of the oropharynx.: A strain of papillomavirus that can infect the skin and mucous membranes of humans.: A condition or state at a particular time.: Not known, not observed, not recorded, or refused.: A carcinoma arising from squamous epithelial cells.  Morphologically, it is characterized by the proliferation of atypical, often pleomorphic squamous cells.  Squamous cell carcinomas are graded by the degree of cellular differentiation as well, moderately, or poorly differentiated.  Well differentiated carcinomas are usually associated with keratin production and the presence of intercellular bridges between adjacent cells.  Representative examples are lung squamous cell carcinoma, skin squamous cell carcinoma, and cervical squamous cell carcinoma.

Concepts.definition: Carcinoma, predominantly squamous cell, arising from the epithelial cells of the oropharynx.
A strain of papillomavirus that can infect the skin and mucous membranes of humans.
A condition or state at a particular time.
Not known, observed, recorded; or reported as unknown by the data contributor.

A carcinoma arising from squamous epithelial cells.  Morphologically, it is characterized by the proliferation of atypical, often pleomorphic squamous cells.  Squamous cell carcinomas are graded by the degree of cellular differentiation as well, moderately, or poorly differentiated.  Well differentiated carcinomas are usually associated with keratin production and the presence of intercellular bridges between adjacent cells.  Representative examples are lung squamous cell carcinoma, skin squamous cell carcinoma, and cervical squamous cell carcinoma.

PermissibleValues.value: Poorly differentiated neuroendocrine carcinoma, large cell
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Large Cell Neuroendocrine Carcinoma Poorly Differentiated

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Large Cell Neuroendocrine Carcinoma Poorly Differentiated
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A usually aggressive carcinoma composed of large malignant cells which display neuroendocrine characteristics. It is characterized by the presence of high mitotic activity and necrotic changes. The vast majority of cases are positive for neuron-specific enolase. Representative examples include lung, breast, cervical, and thymic neuroendocrine carcinomas.: Describes tumor cells that generally have lost most of the appearance of normal cells. They tend to grow and spread.

Concepts.definition: An aggressive, high-grade, and poorly differentiated carcinoma with neuroendocrine differentiation. It is composed of malignant large cells.
Describes tumor cells that generally have lost most of the appearance of normal cells. They tend to grow and spread.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A melanoma that arises from a mucosal site.

Concepts.definition: A melanoma that arises from a mucosal site.

PermissibleValues.value: Poorly differentiated neuroendocrine carcinoma, small cell

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Describes tumor cells that generally have lost most of the appearance of normal cells. They tend to grow and spread.: A neuroendocrine carcinoma composed of small malignant cells which are often said to resemble "oat cells" under the microscope.  Small cell carcinoma most often affects the lungs.  Clinically, this is often a rapidly growing cancer that spreads to distant sites early.

Concepts.definition: Describes tumor cells that generally have lost most of the appearance of normal cells. They tend to grow and spread.
An aggressive, high-grade, and poorly differentiated carcinoma with neuroendocrine differentiation. It is composed of malignant small cells.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A malignant tumor composed of a mixture of carcinomatous and sarcomatous elements.

Concepts.definition: A malignant tumor composed of a mixture of carcinomatous and sarcomatous elements.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An infiltrating malignant epithelial neoplasm characterized by the presence of atypical cells with myoepithelial differentiation. Representative examples include malignant breast myoepithelioma and salivary gland myoepithelial carcinoma.

Concepts.definition: An infiltrating malignant tumor characterized by the presence of atypical cells with myoepithelial differentiation. Representative examples include malignant breast myoepithelioma and salivary gland myoepithelial carcinoma.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Something regarded as a normative example.: A carcinoma arising from squamous epithelial cells.  Morphologically, it is characterized by the proliferation of atypical, often pleomorphic squamous cells.  Squamous cell carcinomas are graded by the degree of cellular differentiation as well, moderately, or poorly differentiated.  Well differentiated carcinomas are usually associated with keratin production and the presence of intercellular bridges between adjacent cells.  Representative examples are lung squamous cell carcinoma, skin squamous cell carcinoma, and cervical squamous cell carcinoma.

Concepts.definition: Something regarded as a normative example.

A carcinoma arising from squamous epithelial cells.  Morphologically, it is characterized by the proliferation of atypical, often pleomorphic squamous cells.  Squamous cell carcinomas are graded by the degree of cellular differentiation as well, moderately, or poorly differentiated.  Well differentiated carcinomas are usually associated with keratin production and the presence of intercellular bridges between adjacent cells.  Representative examples are lung squamous cell carcinoma, skin squamous cell carcinoma, and cervical squamous cell carcinoma.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A high grade adenocarcinoma that arises from the salivary glands. The vast majority of cases have been described in the parotid gland.  It is characterized by the presence of malignant oncocytes.  It recurs and metastasizes to regional or distant anatomic sites.

Concepts.definition: A high grade adenocarcinoma that arises from the salivary glands. The vast majority of cases have been described in the parotid gland.  It is characterized by the presence of malignant oncocytes.  It recurs and metastasizes to regional or distant anatomic sites.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An adenocarcinoma characterized by the presence of large malignant epithelial cells with abundant granular eosinophilic cytoplasm (oncocytes). Representative examples include thyroid gland oncocytic follicular carcinoma, oncocytic breast carcinoma, and salivary gland oncocytic carcinoma.

Concepts.definition: An adenocarcinoma characterized by the presence of large malignant epithelial cells with abundant granular eosinophilic cytoplasm (oncocytes). Representative examples include thyroid gland oncocytic follicular carcinoma, oncocytic breast carcinoma, and salivary gland oncocytic carcinoma.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An adenocarcinoma that arises from the sinonasal tract. It is characterized by the absence of features that resemble intestinal adenocarcinoma.

Concepts.definition: An adenocarcinoma that arises from the sinonasal tract. It is characterized by the absence of features that resemble intestinal adenocarcinoma.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Sinonasal Adenocarcinoma, Intestinal-Type with Mixed Pattern

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Sinonasal Adenocarcinoma, Intestinal-Type with Mixed Pattern
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An intestinal-type adenocarcinoma that arises from the sinonasal tract. It is characterized by the presence of a mixture of growth patterns.

Concepts.longName: Sinonasal Adenocarcinoma, Intestinal-Type with Mixed Pattern
Concepts.definition: An intestinal-type adenocarcinoma that arises from the sinonasal tract. It is characterized by the presence of a mixture of growth patterns.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Sinonasal Adenocarcinoma, Intestinal-Type with Mucinous Pattern

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Sinonasal Adenocarcinoma, Intestinal-Type with Mucinous Pattern
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An intestinal-type adenocarcinoma that arises from the sinonasal tract. It is characterized by the presence of malignant glandular cells with intracytoplasmic mucin.

Concepts.longName: Sinonasal Adenocarcinoma, Intestinal-Type with Mucinous Pattern
Concepts.definition: An intestinal-type adenocarcinoma that arises from the sinonasal tract. It is characterized by the presence of malignant glandular cells with intracytoplasmic mucin.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Sinonasal Adenocarcinoma, Intestinal-Type with Solid Pattern

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Sinonasal Adenocarcinoma, Intestinal-Type with Solid Pattern
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An intestinal-type adenocarcinoma that arises from the sinonasal tract. It is characterized by the presence of a solid growth pattern.

Concepts.longName: Sinonasal Adenocarcinoma, Intestinal-Type with Solid Pattern
Concepts.definition: An intestinal-type adenocarcinoma that arises from the sinonasal tract. It is characterized by the presence of a solid growth pattern.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Sinonasal Adenocarcinoma, Intestinal-Type with Colonic Pattern

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Sinonasal Adenocarcinoma, Intestinal-Type with Colonic Pattern
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An intestinal-type adenocarcinoma that arises from the sinonasal tract. It is characterized by the presence of a tubuloglandular growth pattern.

Concepts.longName: Sinonasal Adenocarcinoma, Intestinal-Type with Colonic Pattern
Concepts.definition: An intestinal-type adenocarcinoma that arises from the sinonasal tract. It is characterized by the presence of a tubuloglandular growth pattern.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Sinonasal Adenocarcinoma, Intestinal-Type with Papillary Pattern

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Sinonasal Adenocarcinoma, Intestinal-Type with Papillary Pattern
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An intestinal-type adenocarcinoma that arises from the sinonasal tract. It is characterized by the presence of a papillary growth pattern.

Concepts.longName: Sinonasal Adenocarcinoma, Intestinal-Type with Papillary Pattern
Concepts.definition: An intestinal-type adenocarcinoma that arises from the sinonasal tract. It is characterized by the presence of a papillary growth pattern.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A squamous cell carcinoma of the sinonasal tract characterized by a plexiform or ribbon-like growth pattern, cytological atypia, and lack of histological evidence of keratinization.

Concepts.definition: A squamous cell carcinoma of the sinonasal tract characterized by a plexiform or ribbon-like growth pattern, cytological atypia, and lack of histological evidence of keratinization.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: p16INK4a Negative Oropharyngeal Squamous Cell Carcinoma

ValueMeaning.preferredName: p16INK4a Negative Oropharyngeal Squamous Cell Carcinoma
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An oropharyngeal squamous cell carcinoma which is negative for p16INK4a by immunohistochemistry. This negative immunohistochemistry result does not exclude human papillomavirus infection.

Concepts.definition: An oropharyngeal squamous cell carcinoma which is negative for p16INK4a by immunohistochemistry. This negative immunohistochemistry result does not exclude human papillomavirus infection.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Human Papillomavirus Positive Oropharyngeal Squamous Cell Carcinoma

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Human Papillomavirus Positive Oropharyngeal Squamous Cell Carcinoma
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A squamous cell carcinoma associated with human papilloma type 16 virus, arising from the oropharynx.

Concepts.longName: Oropharyngeal Human Papillomavirus-Related Squamous Cell Carcinoma
Concepts.definition: A squamous cell carcinoma that arises from the oropharynx and is associated with human papillomavirus type 16 infection.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Marginal Zone Lymphoma Not Otherwise Specified

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Marginal Zone Lymphoma Not Otherwise Specified
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A usually indolent mature B-cell lymphoma, arising from the marginal zone of lymphoid tissues.  It is characterized by the presence of small to medium sized atypical lymphocytes.  It comprises three entities, according to the anatomic sites involved: extranodal marginal zone B-cell lymphoma of mucosa-associated lymphoid tissue, which affects extranodal sites (most often stomach, lung, skin, and ocular adnexa); nodal marginal zone B-cell lymphoma, which affects lymph nodes without evidence of extranodal disease; and splenic marginal zone B-cell lymphoma, which affects the spleen and splenic hilar lymph nodes, bone marrow, and often the peripheral blood.: Not characterized in any other way.

Concepts.definition: A usually indolent mature B-cell lymphoma, arising from the marginal zone of lymphoid tissues.  It is characterized by the presence of small to medium sized atypical lymphocytes.  It comprises three entities, according to the anatomic sites involved: extranodal marginal zone B-cell lymphoma of mucosa-associated lymphoid tissue, which affects extranodal sites (most often stomach, lung, skin, and ocular adnexa); nodal marginal zone B-cell lymphoma, which affects lymph nodes without evidence of extranodal disease; and splenic marginal zone B-cell lymphoma, which affects the spleen and splenic hilar lymph nodes, bone marrow, and often the peripheral blood.
Not characterized in any other way.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Chronic Lymphocytic Leukemia And/Or Small Lymphocytic Lymphoma

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Chronic Lymphocytic Leukemia And/Or Small Lymphocytic Lymphoma
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The most common type of chronic lymphoid leukemia.  It comprises 90% of chronic lymphoid leukemias in the United States.  Morphologically, the neoplastic cells are small, round B-lymphocytes.  This type of leukemia is not considered to be curable with available therapy. (WHO, 2001): Used to indicate that either or both of two items or options may be valid.: A non-Hodgkin lymphoma composed of monomorphic small, round B-lymphocytes in the lymph nodes.  When the lymphoid process predominantly involves the bone marrow and the peripheral blood it is called chronic lymphocytic leukemia. (WHO, 2001)

Concepts.definition: The most common type of chronic lymphoid leukemia.  It comprises 90% of chronic lymphoid leukemias in the United States.  Morphologically, the neoplastic cells are small, round B-lymphocytes.  This type of leukemia is not considered to be curable with available therapy. (WHO, 2001)
Used to indicate that either or both of two items or options may be valid.

A non-Hodgkin lymphoma composed of monomorphic small, round B-lymphocytes in the lymph nodes.  When the lymphoid process predominantly involves the bone marrow and the peripheral blood it is called chronic lymphocytic leukemia. (WHO, 2001)

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A neoplasm of follicle centre B cells which has at least a partial follicular pattern.  Follicular lymphomas comprise about 35% of adult non-Hodgkin lymphomas in the U.S. and 22% worldwide.  Most patients have widespread disease at diagnosis.  Morphologically, follicular lymphomas are classified as Grade 1, Grade 2, and Grade 3, depending on the percentage of the large lymphocytes present.  The vast majority of cases (70-95%) express the BCL-2 rearrangement [t(14;18)].  Histological grade correlates with prognosis.  Grades 1 and 2 follicular lymphomas are indolent and grade 3 is more aggressive (adapted from WHO, 2001).

Concepts.definition: A neoplasm of follicle centre B cells which has at least a partial follicular pattern.  Follicular lymphomas comprise about 35% of adult non-Hodgkin lymphomas in the U.S. and 22% worldwide.  Most patients have widespread disease at diagnosis.  Morphologically, follicular lymphomas are classified as Grade 1, Grade 2, and Grade 3, depending on the percentage of the large lymphocytes present.  The vast majority of cases (70-95%) express the BCL-2 rearrangement [t(14;18)].  Histological grade correlates with prognosis.  Grades 1 and 2 follicular lymphomas are indolent and grade 3 is more aggressive (adapted from WHO, 2001).

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Used to describe tumor samples that exhibit poorly differentiated or undifferentiated cells. They are generally expected to be fast growing and aggressive.: An adenocarcinoma that arises from the ovary and is characterized by the presence of malignant epithelial cells that, in well differentiated tumors, resemble the epithelium of the fallopian tube or, in poorly differentiated tumors, show anaplastic features and marked nuclear atypia.

Concepts.definition: Used to describe tumor samples that exhibit poorly differentiated or undifferentiated cells. They are generally expected to be fast growing and aggressive.

An adenocarcinoma that arises from the ovary and is characterized by the presence of malignant epithelial cells that, in well differentiated tumors, resemble the epithelium of the fallopian tube or, in poorly differentiated tumors, show anaplastic features and marked nuclear atypia.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A slow-growing serous adenocarcinoma that arises from the ovary.  It usually originates from borderline neoplastic processes or adenofibromas.  It is characterized by the presence of low grade cytologic features and infrequent mitotic figures.

Concepts.definition: A slow-growing serous adenocarcinoma that arises from the ovary.  It usually originates from borderline neoplastic processes or adenofibromas.  It is characterized by the presence of low grade cytologic features and infrequent mitotic figures.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Ovarian Small Cell Carcinoma, Pulmonary Type

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Ovarian Small Cell Carcinoma, Pulmonary Type
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An aggressive small cell neuroendocrine carcinoma that arises from the ovary.  Morphologically, it resembles the small cell carcinoma that arises from the lung.

Concepts.definition: An aggressive small cell neuroendocrine carcinoma that arises from the ovary.  Morphologically, it resembles the small cell carcinoma that arises from the lung.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A malignant germ cell tumor that arises from the ovary and is composed of cytotrophoblasts, syncytiotrophoblasts, and extravillous trophoblasts.  The prognosis is less favorable than gestational choriocarcinoma.

Concepts.definition: A malignant germ cell tumor that arises from the ovary and is composed of cytotrophoblasts, syncytiotrophoblasts, and extravillous trophoblasts.  The prognosis is less favorable than gestational choriocarcinoma.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A highly malignant, primitive form of carcinoma, probably of germinal cell or teratomatous derivation, usually arising in a gonad and rarely in other sites. It is rare in the female ovary, but in the male it accounts for 20% of all testicular tumors. (From Dorland, 27th ed & Holland et al., Cancer Medicine, 3d ed, p1595)

Concepts.definition: A non-seminomatous malignant germ cell tumor characterized by the presence of large germ cells with abundant cytoplasm resembling epithelial cells, geographic necrosis, high mitotic activity, and pseudoglandular and pseudopapillary structures formation. It can arise from the testis, ovary, and extragonadal sites (central nervous system and mediastinum).

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Different than the one(s) previously specified or mentioned.: A neoplasm arising in the ovary or testis. It is composed of granulosa cells, Leydig cells, Sertoli cells, and fibroblasts. Each of these cell types may constitute the only cellular component that is present in the neoplasm or it may be mixed with other cell types in various combinations. The prognosis can not always be predicted on histologic grounds alone. Approximately, 10% of these tumors may metastasize. Representative examples include granulosa cell tumor, Leydig cell tumor, Sertoli cell tumor, and tumors of the thecoma-fibroma group.

Concepts.definition: Different than the one(s) previously specified or mentioned.

A neoplasm arising in the ovary or testis. It is composed of granulosa cells, Leydig cells, Sertoli cells, and fibroblasts. Each of these cell types may constitute the only cellular component that is present in the neoplasm or it may be mixed with other cell types in various combinations. The prognosis can not always be predicted on histologic grounds alone. Approximately, 10% of these tumors may metastasize. Representative examples include granulosa cell tumor, Leydig cell tumor, Sertoli cell tumor, and tumors of the thecoma-fibroma group.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A benign or malignant sex cord-stromal tumor arising from the ovary. It is characterized by the presence of neoplastic Leydig cells. Signs and symptoms include hirsutism, menorrhagia and metrorrhagia. It may be associated with trisomy 8.

Concepts.definition: A benign or malignant sex cord-stromal tumor arising from the ovary. It is characterized by the presence of neoplastic Leydig cells. Signs and symptoms include hirsutism, menorrhagia and metrorrhagia. It may be associated with trisomy 8.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Salivary Gland Low Grade Cribriform Cystadenocarcinoma

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Salivary Gland Low Grade Cribriform Cystadenocarcinoma
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A rare, low-grade adenocarcinoma that arises from the salivary glands.  It is characterized by the presence of cystic structures lined by ductal cells which are arranged in cribriform patterns.  Adjacent ducts show intraductal proliferation.
