Concepts.definition: A rare, low-grade adenocarcinoma that arises from the salivary glands.  It is characterized by the presence of cystic structures lined by ductal cells which are arranged in cribriform patterns.  Adjacent ducts show intraductal proliferation.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Mammary Analog Secretory Carcinoma of Salivary Gland

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Mammary Analog Secretory Carcinoma of Salivary Gland
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A rare, low-grade carcinoma of the salivary gland with favorable clinical outcome.  It usually arises from the parotid gland and less often from the minor salivary glands.  It shares the same histopathologic features and molecular characteristics (ETV6 gene rearrangement) with secretory breast carcinoma.

Concepts.definition: A rare, low-grade carcinoma of the salivary gland with favorable clinical outcome.  It usually arises from the parotid gland and less often from the minor salivary glands.  It shares the same histopathologic features and molecular characteristics (ETV6 gene rearrangement) with secretory breast carcinoma.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Salivary Gland Polymorphous Low Grade Adenocarcinoma

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Salivary Gland Polymorphous Low Grade Adenocarcinoma
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A low grade malignant epithelial neoplasm arising from the salivary gland. It usually arises from the oral cavity, with approximately 60% of the cases involving the palate. The most common presenting sign is a painless mass in the palate. It is characterized by the presence of uniform, small to medium size malignant epithelial cells and an infiltrating pattern. There is a variety of morphologic patterns which may be present within an individual tumor, including lobular, papillary, papillary-cystic, cribriform, and trabecular pattern. It usually has a favorable clinical outcome and a low metastatic potential.

Concepts.definition: A low grade malignant epithelial neoplasm arising from the salivary gland. It usually arises from the oral cavity, with approximately 60% of the cases involving the palate. The most common presenting sign is a painless mass in the palate. It is characterized by the presence of uniform, small to medium size malignant epithelial cells and an infiltrating pattern. There is a variety of morphologic patterns which may be present within an individual tumor, including lobular, papillary, papillary-cystic, cribriform, and trabecular pattern. It usually has a favorable clinical outcome and a low metastatic potential.

PermissibleValues.value: Mucinous tubular and spindle renal cell carcinoma
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Mucinous Tubular and Spindle Cell Carcinoma of the Kidney

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Mucinous Tubular and Spindle Cell Carcinoma of the Kidney
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A low grade carcinoma of the kidney characterized by the presence of tubules which are separated by mucinous stroma. Often the tubular structures have a spindle cell appearance.  Patients are usually asymptomatic and occasionally they may present with hematuria or flank pain.

Concepts.longName: Mucinous Tubular and Spindle Cell Carcinoma of the Kidney
Concepts.definition: A low grade carcinoma of the kidney characterized by the presence of tubules which are separated by mucinous stroma. Often the tubular structures have a spindle cell appearance.  Patients are usually asymptomatic and occasionally they may present with hematuria or flank pain.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Renal Cell Carcinoma with t(6;11);(p21;q12); MALAT1-TFEB

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Renal Cell Carcinoma with t(6;11);(p21;q12); MALAT1-TFEB
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An extremely rare renal cell carcinoma affecting young patients. It is characterized by the presence of the specific chromosomal translocation t(6;11);(p21;q12) which fuses the MALAT1 gene with the TFEB transcription factor gene.

Concepts.definition: A rare renal cell carcinoma affecting young patients. It is characterized by the presence of the chromosomal translocation t(6;11) which fuses the TFEB transcription factor gene, located on chromosome 6, with the MALAT1 gene, located on chromosome 11.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Renal Cell Carcinoma Associated with Xp11.2 Translocations/TFE3 Gene Fusions

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Renal Cell Carcinoma Associated with Xp11.2 Translocations/TFE3 Gene Fusions
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A group of kidney carcinomas characterized by the presence of different translocations involving the chromosome Xp11.2.  These translocations result in the creation of gene fusions involving the TFE3 gene.  Patients are usually children and young adults.  Morphologically, the malignant epithelial cells form papillary patterns.  The clinical behavior of this group of carcinomas is largely unknown.

Concepts.definition: A group of renal cell carcinomas characterized by the presence of different translocations involving the chromosome Xp11.2. These translocations result in the creation of gene fusions involving the TFE3 gene. Patients are usually children and young adults. Morphologically, the malignant epithelial cells form papillary patterns.

PermissibleValues.value: MiT family translocation renal cell carcinoma
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: MiT Family Translocation-Associated Renal Cell Carcinoma

ValueMeaning.preferredName: MiT Family Translocation-Associated Renal Cell Carcinoma
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A renal cell carcinoma (RCC) usually seen in children or young adults. It is characterized by papillary, alveolar and nested growth patterns with clear and eosinophilic cells. The carcinomas range from microscopic lesions to clinically symptomatic tumors. It is associated with translocations/gene fusions involving members of the MiT family of transcription factors, including TFE3 and TFEB. There are two subtypes; RCCs associated with Xp11 translocations and TFE3 gene fusions and RCCs with t(6:11) translocations resulting in MALAT1-TFEB gene fusions.

Concepts.longName: Renal Cell Carcinoma with MiT Translocations
Concepts.definition: A renal cell carcinoma usually seen in children or young adults. It is characterized by papillary, alveolar and nested growth patterns with clear and eosinophilic cells. The carcinomas range from microscopic lesions to clinically symptomatic tumors. It is associated with translocations/gene fusions involving members of the MiT family of transcription factors. There are two subtypes: TFE3-rearranged renal cell carcinoma [Xp11 translocation renal cell carcinoma] and TFEB-rearranged renal cell carcinoma [t(6;11) renal cell carcinoma].

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A recently described type of renal carcinoma, affecting mostly young African-Americans.  It is located in the medulla of the kidney, and follows an aggressive clinical course.  Most reported cases have shown metastatic disease at the time of diagnosis.

Concepts.definition: A type of renal carcinoma affecting mostly young African-Americans.  It is located in the medulla of the kidney, and follows an aggressive clinical course.  Most reported cases have shown metastatic disease at the time of diagnosis.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Carcinoma of the Collecting Ducts of Bellini

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Carcinoma of the Collecting Ducts of Bellini
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Also known as collecting duct carcinoma, this is a rare type of renal carcinoma. It arises from the collecting ducts of the renal medulla, and most authors suggest that this is an aggressive tumor.

Concepts.definition: Also known as collecting duct carcinoma, this is a rare type of renal carcinoma. It arises from the collecting ducts of the renal medulla, and most authors suggest that this is an aggressive tumor.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A papillary renal cell carcinoma characterized by the presence of papillae covered by cells of a higher nuclear grade as compared to type 1 papillary renal cell carcinoma. The cells have eosinophilic cytoplasm and pseudostratified nuclei.

Concepts.definition: A papillary renal cell carcinoma characterized by the presence of papillae covered by cells of a higher nuclear grade as compared to type 1 papillary renal cell carcinoma. The cells have eosinophilic cytoplasm and pseudostratified nuclei.

ValueMeaning.changeDescription: Concept annotation added for UPitt/TCGA.  Ylu, 02/03/2015.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A papillary renal cell carcinoma characterized by the presence of papillae covered by small cells with scant amount of cytoplasm. The cells are arranged in a single layer on the basement membrane of the papillae.

Concepts.definition: A papillary renal cell carcinoma characterized by the presence of papillae covered by small cells with scant amount of cytoplasm. The cells are arranged in a single layer on the basement membrane of the papillae.

ValueMeaning.changeDescription: Concept annotation added for UPitt/TCGA.  Ylu, 02/03/2015.

PermissibleValues.value: Multilocular cystic clear cell renal cell neoplasm of low malignant potential

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A rare type of renal cell carcinoma.  It is a well-circumscribed multicystic mass without solid areas.  The inner lining of the cystic structures is composed of clear cells.

Concepts.longName: Multilocular Cystic Renal Neoplasm of Low Malignant Potential
Concepts.definition: A rare kidney neoplasm of low malignant potential.  It is a well-circumscribed multicystic mass without solid areas.  The inner lining of the cystic structures is composed of clear cells. It usually presents as a unilateral solitary mass.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A malignant epithelial neoplasm of the kidney characterized by the presence of lipid-containing clear cells within a vascular network.  The tumor may metastasize to unusual sites and late metastasis is common.

Concepts.definition: A malignant epithelial neoplasm of the kidney characterized by the presence of lipid-containing clear cells within a vascular network.  The tumor may metastasize to unusual sites and late metastasis is common.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Acantholytic Cuniculatum
A histologic variant of squamous cell carcinoma that arises from the skin. It is characterized by loosening of the intercellular bridges between the malignant cells which results in acantholysis.

Concepts.definition: A histologic variant of squamous cell carcinoma that arises from the skin. It is characterized by loosening of the intercellular bridges between the malignant cells which results in acantholysis.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A small cell or rarely a large cell neuroendocrine carcinoma that arises from the prostate gland.

Concepts.definition: An aggressive, high-grade, and poorly differentiated carcinoma with neuroendocrine differentiation that arises from the prostate gland. The mitotic count is more than 20 per 10 HPF. It is classified as either small or large cell neuroendocrine carcinoma based on the size of the malignant cells, the prominence of the nucleoli, and the amount of cytoplasm.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A state of separation; the act of isolating something; setting something apart from others; marked by separation of or from usually contiguous elements.: An intra-acinar and/or intraductal neoplastic epithelial proliferation in the prostate gland that has some features of high-grade prostatic intraepithelial neoplasia but exhibits much greater architectural and/or cytological atypia, typically associated with high-grade, high-stage prostate carcinoma. (WHO 2016)

Concepts.definition: A state of separation; the act of isolating something; setting something apart from others; marked by separation of or from usually contiguous elements.

An intra-acinar and/or intraductal neoplastic epithelial proliferation in the prostate gland that has some features of high-grade prostatic intraepithelial neoplasia but exhibits much greater architectural and/or cytological atypia, typically associated with high-grade, high-stage prostate carcinoma. (WHO 2016)

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A neuroendocrine carcinoma of the prostate gland with unfavorable prognosis. It is composed of small cells containing neurosecretory granules.

Concepts.definition: A rare small cell neuroendocrine carcinoma that arises from the prostate gland.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A usually aggressive invasive adenocarcinoma of the prostate gland composed of large glands containing tall columnar cells.  The columnar cells have abundant cytoplasm and are reminiscent of endometrial carcinoma.  This type of adenocarcinoma has a tendency to metastasize to the lung and penis.

Concepts.definition: A usually aggressive invasive adenocarcinoma of the prostate gland composed of large glands containing tall columnar cells.  The columnar cells have abundant cytoplasm and are reminiscent of endometrial carcinoma.  This type of adenocarcinoma has a tendency to metastasize to the lung and penis.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A renal cell carcinoma characterized by morphologic features that do not fit easily into one of the other well-defined categories of renal cell carcinoma. Examples of such features include mixtures of morphologic patterns, mucin production, and sarcomatoid morphology.

Concepts.definition: A renal cell carcinoma characterized by morphologic features that do not fit easily into one of the other well-defined categories of renal cell carcinoma. Examples of such features include mixtures of morphologic patterns, mucin production, and sarcomatoid morphology.

PermissibleValues.value: Succinate dehydrogenase (SDH) deficient renal cell carcinoma

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A very rare renal cell carcinoma that usually affects young adults. It is characterized by the presence of vacuolated, eosinophilic to clear neoplastic cells and loss of immunohistochemical expression of succinate dehydrogenase (SDH) B. In most cases germline mutations in an SDH gene (SDHA, SDHB, SDHC, or SDHD gene) are present. It has a relatively good prognosis.

Concepts.definition: A very rare renal cell carcinoma that usually affects young adults. It is characterized by mutations in one of the four subunits of the SDH complex (SDHA, SDHB, SDHC, or SDHD gene). Most frequently, the mutations occur in the SDHB subunit. It has a relatively good prognosis.

PermissibleValues.value: Hereditary leiomyomatosis and renal cell carcinoma-associated renal cell carcinoma
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Hereditary Leiomyomatosis and Renal Cell Cancer

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Hereditary Leiomyomatosis and Renal Cell Cancer
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An autosomal dominant inherited syndrome caused by germline mutations in the FH gene. It is characterized by predisposition to leiomyomas of the skin and uterus, renal cell carcinoma, and leiomyosarcoma of the uterus.

Concepts.longName: Hereditary Leiomyomatosis and Renal Cell Carcinoma
Concepts.definition: An autosomal dominant inherited syndrome caused by germline mutations in the FH gene. It is characterized by predisposition to renal cell carcinoma, leiomyomas of the skin and uterus, and leiomyosarcoma of the uterus.

PermissibleValues.value: Clear cell papillary renal cell carcinoma

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An encapsulated epithelial neoplasm that arises from the kidney. It is composed of cytologically bland epithelial cells with clear cytoplasm forming tubular and papillary patterns. The nuclei are arranged linearly away from the basement membrane. Tumor necrosis, perirenal invasion, and vascular invasion are not present. The clinical course is indolent.

Concepts.definition: An encapsulated epithelial neoplasm that arises from the kidney. It is composed of cytologically bland epithelial cells with clear cytoplasm forming tubular and papillary patterns. The nuclei are arranged linearly away from the basement membrane. Tumor necrosis, perirenal invasion, and vascular invasion are not present. The clinical course is indolent.

PermissibleValues.value: Acquired cystic disease associated renal cell carcinoma
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Acquired Cystic Disease-Associated Renal Cell Carcinoma

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Acquired Cystic Disease-Associated Renal Cell Carcinoma
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The most common renal cell carcinoma that develops in patients with end-stage renal disease and acquired cystic disease.

Concepts.longName: Acquired Cystic Disease-Associated Renal Cell Carcinoma
Concepts.definition: The most common renal cell carcinoma that develops in patients with end-stage renal disease and acquired cystic disease.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A rare, cytologically high grade carcinoma that arises from the renal parenchyma. It is characterized by the presence of prominently dilated cystic spaces in a bland, fibrotic stroma. The lining cells have large irregular nuclei with prominent nucleoli and abundant eosinophilic cytoplasm. Necrosis and mitotic figures are not present. It rarely metastasizes.

Concepts.definition: A rare, cytologically high grade carcinoma that arises from the renal parenchyma. It is characterized by the presence of prominently dilated cystic spaces in a bland, fibrotic stroma. The lining cells have large irregular nuclei with prominent nucleoli and abundant eosinophilic cytoplasm. Necrosis and mitotic figures are not present. It rarely metastasizes.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A benign, borderline, or malignant fibroepithelial neoplasm arising from the breast and rarely the prostate gland.  It may recur following resection.  The recurrence rates are higher for borderline and malignant phyllodes tumors.  In borderline and malignant phyllodes tumors metastases to distant anatomic sites can occur.  The incidence of metastases is higher in malignant phyllodes tumors.

Concepts.definition: A benign, borderline, or malignant fibroepithelial neoplasm arising from the breast and rarely the prostate gland.  It may recur following resection.  The recurrence rates are higher for borderline and malignant phyllodes tumors.  In borderline and malignant phyllodes tumors metastases to distant anatomic sites can occur.  The incidence of metastases is higher in malignant phyllodes tumors.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A rare adenocarcinoma of the major and minor salivary glands, originating from basaloid, myoepithelial and ductal cells.  While morphologically resembling basal cell carcinomas, it is a distinct entity.  The tumor is not encapsulated, may invade locally, and less frequently may metastasize.  It usually occurs in older patients.

Concepts.definition: A rare adenocarcinoma of the major and minor salivary glands, originating from basaloid, myoepithelial and ductal cells.  While morphologically resembling basal cell carcinomas, it is a distinct entity.  The tumor is not encapsulated, may invade locally, and less frequently may metastasize.  It usually occurs in older patients.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A malignant neoplasm which occurs mostly in the major salivary glands (most frequently in the parotid gland), but also in the minor salivary glands of the oral mucosa and the tracheobronchial tree. It is characterized by the presence of ductal structures which are lined by an inner layer of cuboidal epithelial-type cells and an outer layer of myoepithelial cells with clear or eosinophilic cytoplasm.

Concepts.definition: A malignant neoplasm which occurs mostly in the major salivary glands (most frequently in the parotid gland), but also in the minor salivary glands of the oral mucosa and the tracheobronchial tree. It is characterized by the presence of ductal structures which are lined by an inner layer of cuboidal epithelial-type cells and an outer layer of myoepithelial cells with clear or eosinophilic cytoplasm.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An aggressive, high grade adenocarcinoma that arises from the salivary glands. It usually affects elderly males and presents as a rapidly enlarging mass. It metastasizes to regional lymph nodes and distant anatomic sites.

Concepts.definition: An aggressive, high grade adenocarcinoma that arises from the salivary glands. It usually affects elderly males and presents as a rapidly enlarging mass. It metastasizes to regional lymph nodes and distant anatomic sites.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Spindle Cell (Sarcomatoid) Squamous Cell Skin Carcinoma

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Spindle Cell (Sarcomatoid) Squamous Cell Skin Carcinoma
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A squamous cell carcinoma of the skin with a prominent spindle cell component.

Concepts.definition: A squamous cell carcinoma of the skin with a prominent spindle cell component.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A squamous cell carcinoma characterized by the presence of cells with hyperchromatic nuclei, scant amount of cytoplasm, and peripheral nuclear palisading.

Concepts.definition: A squamous cell carcinoma characterized by the presence of cells with hyperchromatic nuclei, scant amount of cytoplasm, and peripheral nuclear palisading.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Being comprised of mixed attributes or parts.: Flat cell that looks like a fish scale under a microscope. These cells cover inside and outside surfaces of the body. They are found in the tissues that form the surface of the skin, the lining of the hollow organs of the body (such as the bladder, kidney, and uterus), and the passages of the respiratory and digestive tracts.: A malignant tumor arising from epithelial cells. Carcinomas that arise from glandular epithelium are called adenocarcinomas, those that arise from squamous epithelium are called squamous cell carcinomas, and those that arise from transitional epithelium are called transitional cell carcinomas. Morphologically, the malignant epithelial cells may display abnormal mitotic figures, anaplasia, and necrosis. Carcinomas are graded by the degree of cellular differentiation as well, moderately, or poorly differentiated. Carcinomas invade the surrounding tissues and tend to metastasize to other anatomic sites. Lung carcinoma, skin carcinoma, breast carcinoma, colon carcinoma, and prostate carcinoma are the most frequently seen carcinomas.

Concepts.definition: Being comprised of mixed attributes or parts.

Flat cell that looks like a fish scale under a microscope. These cells cover inside and outside surfaces of the body. They are found in the tissues that form the surface of the skin, the lining of the hollow organs of the body (such as the bladder, kidney, and uterus), and the passages of the respiratory and digestive tracts.

A malignant tumor arising from epithelial cells. Carcinomas that arise from glandular epithelium are called adenocarcinomas, those that arise from squamous epithelium are called squamous cell carcinomas, and those that arise from transitional epithelium are called transitional cell carcinomas. Morphologically, the malignant epithelial cells may display abnormal mitotic figures, anaplasia, and necrosis. Carcinomas are graded by the degree of cellular differentiation as well, moderately, or poorly differentiated. Carcinomas invade the surrounding tissues and tend to metastasize to other anatomic sites. Lung carcinoma, skin carcinoma, breast carcinoma, colon carcinoma, and prostate carcinoma are the most frequently seen carcinomas.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A rare malignant heterologous neoplasm with skeletal muscle differentiation arising from the uterine corpus. It usually manifests with vaginal bleeding. The prognosis is poor.

Concepts.definition: A rare malignant heterologous neoplasm with skeletal muscle differentiation arising from the uterine corpus. It usually manifests with vaginal bleeding. The prognosis is poor.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A malignant tumor arising from the epithelium that lines the cavity of the uterine body.  The vast majority of endometrial carcinomas are adenocarcinomas; squamous cell and adenosquamous carcinomas represent a minority of the cases.  Endometrioid adenocarcinoma is the most frequently seen variant of endometrial adenocarcinoma.  Uterine bleeding is an initial clinical sign.  The prognosis depends on the stage of the tumor, the depth of myometrial wall invasion, and the degree of differentiation.

Concepts.definition: A malignant tumor arising from the epithelium that lines the cavity of the uterine body.  The vast majority of endometrial carcinomas are adenocarcinomas; squamous cell and adenosquamous carcinomas represent a minority of the cases.  Endometrioid adenocarcinoma is the most frequently seen variant of endometrial adenocarcinoma.  Uterine bleeding is an initial clinical sign.  The prognosis depends on the stage of the tumor, the depth of myometrial wall invasion, and the degree of differentiation.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A carcinoma that arises from the endometrium and is characterized by the presence of an undifferentiated carcinomatous component and a second component of either FIGO grade 1 or 2 endometrioid carcinoma.

Concepts.definition: A carcinoma that arises from the endometrium and is characterized by the presence of an undifferentiated carcinomatous component and a second component of either FIGO grade 1 or 2 endometrioid carcinoma.

PermissibleValues.value: Mixed cell carcinoma (specify types and percentages)

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An adenocarcinoma that arises from the endometrium and is characterized by the presence of both type I and type II endometrial adenocarcinoma components.  The minor component constitutes at least 5% of the entire tumor.

Concepts.definition: An adenocarcinoma that arises from the endometrium and is characterized by the presence of both type I and type II endometrial adenocarcinoma components.  The minor component constitutes at least 5% of the entire tumor.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A low grade malignant neoplasm characterized by the presence of a benign epithelial component (tubular and cleft-like glands) and a low grade sarcomatous component that contains varying amounts of fibrous and smooth muscle tissues. In a minority of cases, the sarcomatous component contains heterologous elements including striated muscle, cartilage, and fat. It occurs in the uterine corpus, ovary, fallopian tube, cervix, and vagina. It may recur and in a minority of cases may metastasize to distant anatomic sites.: A histopathologic finding characterized by the presence of malignant cells of connective tissue origin in a tumor sample.  Examples of connective tissue cells that can undergo malignant transformation include smooth and skeletal muscle cells, adipose tissue cells, osteocytes, and chondrocytes.

Concepts.definition: A low grade malignant neoplasm characterized by the presence of a benign epithelial component (tubular and cleft-like glands) and a low grade sarcomatous component that contains varying amounts of fibrous and smooth muscle tissues. In a minority of cases, the sarcomatous component contains heterologous elements including striated muscle, cartilage, and fat. It occurs in the uterine corpus, ovary, fallopian tube, cervix, and vagina. It may recur and in a minority of cases may metastasize to distant anatomic sites.

A histopathologic finding characterized by the presence of malignant cells of connective tissue origin in a tumor sample.  Examples of connective tissue cells that can undergo malignant transformation include smooth and skeletal muscle cells, adipose tissue cells, osteocytes, and chondrocytes.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Refers to abnormal cell activity manifested by decreased control over growth and function, causing tumor growth or spread into surrounding tissue and adverse effects to the host.: A perivascular cell with abundant clear or eosinophilic cytoplasm that contains glycogen. -- 2005: A benign or malignant tissue growth resulting from uncontrolled cell proliferation. Benign neoplastic cells resemble normal cells without exhibiting significant cytologic atypia, while malignant cells exhibit overt signs such as dysplastic features, atypical mitotic figures, necrosis, nuclear pleomorphism, and anaplasia. Representative examples of benign neoplasms include papillomas, cystadenomas, and lipomas; malignant neoplasms include carcinomas, sarcomas, lymphomas, and leukemias.

Concepts.definition: Refers to abnormal cell activity manifested by decreased control over growth and function, causing tumor growth or spread into surrounding tissue and adverse effects to the host.
A perivascular cell with abundant clear or eosinophilic cytoplasm that contains glycogen. -- 2005

A benign or malignant tissue growth resulting from uncontrolled cell proliferation. Benign neoplastic cells resemble normal cells without exhibiting significant cytologic atypia, while malignant cells exhibit overt signs such as dysplastic features, atypical mitotic figures, necrosis, nuclear pleomorphism, and anaplasia. Representative examples of benign neoplasms include papillomas, cystadenomas, and lipomas; malignant neoplasms include carcinomas, sarcomas, lymphomas, and leukemias.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A rare aggressive malignant mesenchymal neoplasm arising from skeletal muscle. It usually occurs in children and young adults. Only a small percentage of tumors arise in the skeletal muscle of the extremities. The majority arise in other anatomical sites.

Concepts.definition: A rare aggressive malignant mesenchymal neoplasm arising from skeletal muscle. It usually occurs in children and young adults. Only a small percentage of tumors arise in the skeletal muscle of the extremities. The majority arise in other anatomic sites.

It may recur and in a minority of cases may metastasize to distant anatomic sites.: A morphologic finding indicating the presence of tissues that do not normally occur in the specific anatomic site or are found admixed with a neoplastic cellular infiltrate of a different cellular origin.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A rare, high grade sarcoma that arises from the endometrial stroma or myometrium without a specific type of differentiation. It was previously also known as high grade endometrial stromal sarcoma. In 2014, high grade endometrial stromal sarcoma was reclassified and is currently considered a distinct and rare neoplasm. Undifferentiated uterine sarcoma has a worse prognosis.

Concepts.definition: A rare, high grade sarcoma that arises from the endometrial stroma or myometrium without a specific type of differentiation. It was previously also known as high grade endometrial stromal sarcoma. In 2014, high grade endometrial stromal sarcoma was reclassified and is currently considered a distinct and rare neoplasm. Undifferentiated uterine sarcoma has a worse prognosis.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Cribriform Adenocarcinoma of Minor Salivary Gland

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Cribriform Adenocarcinoma of Minor Salivary Gland
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A minor salivary gland adenocarcinoma characterized by a cribriform pattern. It often metastasizes to the neck lymph nodes.

Concepts.longName: Cribriform Adenocarcinoma of Minor Salivary Gland
Concepts.definition: A minor salivary gland adenocarcinoma characterized by a cribriform pattern. It often metastasizes to the neck lymph nodes.

PermissibleValues.value: Endometrial stromal sarcoma with glandular elements

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A malignant mesenchymal neoplasm that affects the uterine corpus, and rarely, the ovaries, cervix, and vagina. In the uterine corpus it is classified as low grade or high grade endometrial stromal sarcoma. In the remainder of the anatomic sites it is classified as low grade endometrioid stromal sarcoma.: A microscopic finding indicating the presence of cells with glandular differentiation in a tumor sample.

Concepts.definition: A malignant mesenchymal neoplasm that affects the uterine corpus, and rarely, the ovaries, cervix, and vagina. In the uterine corpus it is classified as low grade or high grade endometrial stromal sarcoma. In the remainder of the anatomic sites it is classified as low grade endometrioid stromal sarcoma.
A microscopic finding indicating the presence of cells with glandular differentiation in a tumor sample.

PermissibleValues.value: Endometrial stromal sarcoma with sex cord elements
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Endometrioid Stromal Sarcoma Sex Cord-Like Pattern

PermissibleValues.value: Endometrial stromal sarcoma with smooth muscle differentiation
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Endometrioid Stromal Sarcoma Smooth Muscle Cell Cellular Differentiation

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Endometrioid Stromal Sarcoma Smooth Muscle Cell Cellular Differentiation
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A malignant mesenchymal neoplasm that affects the uterine corpus, and rarely, the ovaries, cervix, and vagina. In the uterine corpus it is classified as low grade or high grade endometrial stromal sarcoma. In the remainder of the anatomic sites it is classified as low grade endometrioid stromal sarcoma.: An elongated spindle-shaped contractile cell, peculiar to an involuntary muscle, containing a single nucleus and longitudinally arranged myofibrils.: In cancer, refers to how mature (developed) the cancer cells are in a tumor. Differentiated tumor cells resemble normal cells and tend to grow and spread at a slower rate than undifferentiated or poorly differentiated tumor cells, which lack the structure and function of normal cells and grow uncontrollably.

Concepts.definition: A malignant mesenchymal neoplasm that affects the uterine corpus, and rarely, the ovaries, cervix, and vagina. In the uterine corpus it is classified as low grade or high grade endometrial stromal sarcoma. In the remainder of the anatomic sites it is classified as low grade endometrioid stromal sarcoma.
An elongated spindle-shaped contractile cell, peculiar to an involuntary muscle, containing a single nucleus and longitudinally arranged myofibrils.

In cancer, refers to how mature (developed) the cancer cells are in a tumor. Differentiated tumor cells resemble normal cells and tend to grow and spread at a slower rate than undifferentiated or poorly differentiated tumor cells, which lack the structure and function of normal cells and grow uncontrollably.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A malignant, infiltrating mesenchymal tumor arising from the uterine corpus, cervix, vagina, and the ovary. Based on its morphologic characteristics, it is classified as either a low grade or an undifferentiated (high grade) stromal sarcoma. The low grade endometrioid stromal sarcoma is characterized by the presence of oval to spindle-shape cells that resemble the cells of the endometrial stroma, without evidence of significant atypia and pleomorphism. Numerous small vessels are also present. The undifferentiated stromal sarcoma is characterized by an aggressive clinical course, the presence of significant cellular atypia, pleomorphism, and high mitotic activity.

Concepts.definition: A malignant mesenchymal neoplasm that affects the uterine corpus, and rarely, the ovaries, cervix, and vagina. In the uterine corpus it is classified as low grade or high grade endometrial stromal sarcoma. In the remainder of the anatomic sites it is classified as low grade endometrioid stromal sarcoma.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A morphologic variant of leiomyosarcoma characterized by the presence of cellular pleomorphism, malignant cells with large nuclei, and a myxoid stroma.

Concepts.definition: A morphologic variant of leiomyosarcoma characterized by the presence of cellular pleomorphism, malignant cells with large nuclei, and a myxoid stroma.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A morphologic variant of leiomyosarcoma characterized by the presence of epithelioid round cells with eosinophilic to clear cytoplasm.

Concepts.definition: A morphologic variant of leiomyosarcoma characterized by the presence of epithelioid round cells with eosinophilic to clear cytoplasm.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An aggressive malignant tumor of the female reproductive system, affecting predominantly elderly menopausal women.  The endometrium and ovary are the most common sites of tumor origin.  Morphologically, it is a high grade tumor, composed of carcinomatous and sarcomatous elements.

Concepts.definition: An aggressive malignant tumor of the female reproductive system, affecting predominantly elderly menopausal women.  The endometrium and ovary are the most common sites of tumor origin.  Morphologically, it is a high grade tumor, composed of carcinomatous and sarcomatous elements.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A precursor of endometrial serous adenocarcinoma characterized by the replacement of the normal endometrial cells by malignant glandular cells that resemble the malignant cells of invasive serous adenocarcinoma. The endometrial neoplastic process is non-invasive. It may coexist with invasive endometrial adenocarcinoma or can be associated with metastases outside the uterus, in the absence of invasive endometrial carcinoma.

Concepts.definition: A precursor of endometrial serous adenocarcinoma characterized by the replacement of the normal endometrial cells by malignant glandular cells that resemble the malignant cells of invasive serous adenocarcinoma. The endometrial neoplastic process is non-invasive. It may coexist with invasive endometrial adenocarcinoma or can be associated with metastases outside the uterus, in the absence of invasive endometrial carcinoma.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A rare, slow-growing, low-grade soft tissue sarcoma arising from the sinonasal tract. It presents with non-specific obstructive nasal symptoms. Morphologically, it is an infiltrative, cellular spindle cell neoplasm. It is associated with rearrangement of the PAX3 gene.

Concepts.definition: A rare, slow-growing, low-grade soft tissue sarcoma arising from the sinonasal tract. It presents with non-specific obstructive nasal symptoms. Morphologically, it is an infiltrative, cellular spindle cell neoplasm. It is associated with rearrangement of the PAX3 gene.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An endometrioid adenocarcinoma arising from the endometrium. Morphologically it is characterized by the presence of malignant glandular cells containing glycogen vacuoles which are usually subnuclear and reminiscent of early secretory endometrium.

Concepts.definition: An endometrioid adenocarcinoma arising from the endometrium. Morphologically it is characterized by the presence of malignant glandular cells containing glycogen vacuoles which are usually subnuclear and reminiscent of early secretory endometrium.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A primary endometrioid adenocarcinoma of the endometrium characterized by the presence of numerous finger-like villi lined by neoplastic columnar cells.

Concepts.definition: A primary endometrioid adenocarcinoma of the endometrium characterized by the presence of numerous finger-like villi lined by neoplastic columnar cells.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A primary carcinoma of the endometrium characterized by the presence of malignant squamous cells.

Concepts.definition: A primary carcinoma of the endometrium characterized by the presence of malignant squamous cells.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Not characterized in any other way.: A usually malignant and aggressive neoplasm of the mesothelium which is often associated with exposure to asbestos.

Concepts.definition: Not characterized in any other way.
A usually malignant and aggressive neoplasm of the mesothelium which is often associated with exposure to asbestos.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Type 1 (peripheral) neurofibromatosis (von Recklinghausen's disease), is the most common type of neurofibromatosis.  It is characterized clinically by cutaneous and subcutaneous tumors with patches of hyperpigmentation. The hyperpigmented skin areas, are present from birth and found anywhere on the body surface.  They can vary markedly in size and color.  The dark brown areas are called cafe-au-lait spots. The multiple cutaneous and subcutaneous tumors are nerve sheath neoplasms, called neurofibromas.  They can develop anywhere along the peripheral nerve fibers. Neurofibromas can become quite large, causing a major disfigurement, eroding bone, and compressing various peripheral nerve structures.  Type 1 neurofibromatosis has dominant inheritance, with a gene locus on the proximal long arm of chromosome 17.

Concepts.definition: The most common type of neurofibromatosis.  It is characterized clinically by cutaneous and subcutaneous tumors with patches of hyperpigmentation. The hyperpigmented skin areas, are present from birth and found anywhere on the body surface.  They can vary markedly in size and color.  The dark brown areas are called cafe-au-lait spots. The multiple cutaneous and subcutaneous tumors are nerve sheath tumors, called neurofibromas.  They can develop anywhere along the peripheral nerve fibers. Neurofibromas can become quite large, causing a major disfigurement, eroding bone, and compressing various peripheral nerve structures.  Type 1 neurofibromatosis has dominant inheritance, with a gene locus on the proximal long arm of chromosome 17.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An autosomal dominant disorder caused by mutations in the NF2 tumor suppressor gene.  It is characterized by the development of peripheral and central nervous system tumors including acoustic schwannomas, neurofibromas, gliomas, and meningiomas.

Concepts.definition: An autosomal dominant disorder caused by mutations in the NF2 tumor suppressor gene.  It is characterized by the development of peripheral and central nervous system tumors including acoustic schwannomas, neurofibromas, gliomas, and meningiomas.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A rare genetic disorder characterized by the presence of multiple schwannomas.

Concepts.definition: Rare genetic disorder caused by mutations in the SMARCB1 and LZTR1 genes. It is characterized by the presence of multiple Schwannomas.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A small round cell tumor that lacks morphologic, immunohistochemical, and electron microscopic evidence of neuroectodermal differentiation. It represents one of the two ends of the spectrum called Ewing sarcoma/peripheral neuroectodermal tumor. It affects mostly males under age 20, and it can occur in soft tissue or bone. Pain and the presence of a mass are the most common clinical symptoms.

Concepts.definition: A small round cell tumor that lacks morphologic, immunohistochemical, and electron microscopic evidence of neuroectodermal differentiation. It represents one of the two ends of the spectrum called Ewing sarcoma/peripheral neuroectodermal tumor. It affects mostly males under age 20, and it can occur in soft tissue or bone. Pain and the presence of a mass are the most common clinical symptoms.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A rare neoplasm of small B-lymphocytes with "hairy" projections in bone marrow, spleen and peripheral blood.  Most patients are middle-aged to elderly adults and present with splenomegaly and pancytopenia. (WHO, 2001) -- 2003

Concepts.definition: A neoplasm of small B-lymphocytes with "hairy" projections in bone marrow, spleen, and peripheral blood.  Most patients present with splenomegaly and pancytopenia. (WHO, 2001)

PermissibleValues.value: Kaposi-sarcoma Associated Herpesvirus (KSHV) Inflammatory Cytokine Syndrome

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A syndrome caused by Kaposi sarcoma-associated herpesvirus (KSHV) infection. It manifests with fever, weight loss, and fluid retention in the legs or abdomen. Patients are at risk of developing KSHV-related cancers including Kaposi sarcoma and lymphoma.

Concepts.definition: A syndrome caused by Kaposi sarcoma-associated herpesvirus (KSHV) infection. It manifests with fever, weight loss, and fluid retention in the legs or abdomen. Patients are at risk of developing KSHV-related cancers including Kaposi sarcoma and lymphoma.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Multicentric Castleman disease associated with HHV8 infection.

Concepts.definition: Multicentric Castleman disease associated with HHV8 infection.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: No value exists.

Concepts.definition: No value exists.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A neoplasm arising from paraganglia located along the sympathetic or parasympathetic nerves.  Infrequently, it may arise outside the usual distribution of the sympathetic and parasympathetic paraganglia.  Tumors arising from the adrenal gland medulla are called pheochromocytomas.  Morphologically, paragangliomas usually display a nesting (Zellballen) growth pattern.  There are no reliable morphologic criteria to distinguish between benign and malignant paragangliomas. Concepts.definition: A neoplasm arising from paraganglia located along the sympathetic or parasympathetic nerves.  Infrequently, it may arise outside the usual distribution of the sympathetic and parasympathetic paraganglia.  Tumors arising from the adrenal gland medulla are called pheochromocytomas.  Morphologically, paragangliomas usually display a nesting (Zellballen) growth pattern.  There are no reliable morphologic criteria to distinguish between benign and malignant paragangliomas.  The only definitive indicator of malignancy is the presence of regional or distant metastases.

RepresentationTerm.preferredDefinition: A tumor composed of atypical neoplastic, often pleomorphic cells that invade other tissues.
